7
00:06:00,193 --> 00:06:06,406
This Army being raised to quell this,
uh, rebellion and to preserve the Union.

8
00:06:08,868 --> 00:06:12,913
l assume this Army is to be used
to invade those areas. . .

9
00:06:13,081 --> 00:06:15,791
. ..to eliminate the rebellion by force.

10
00:06:15,958 --> 00:06:20,504
Yes, sir, the Federal government
has been challenged by these rebels. . .

11
00:06:20,671 --> 00:06:25,675
. ..who have been most effective in changing
the sentiments of state legislatures...

12
00:06:26,219 --> 00:06:31,139
. ..challenging our Constitution
and challenging our central government.

13
00:06:31,307 --> 00:06:36,228
The attack on Fort Sumter
cannot be ignored.

14
00:06:36,396 --> 00:06:40,107
General, my home is right there
across the Potomac.

15
00:06:40,274 --> 00:06:43,652
Why, you can see Arlington House
from your front door.

16
00:06:44,153 --> 00:06:47,864
My family is spread all
over this part of Virginia.

17
00:06:48,032 --> 00:06:53,036
lf you invade the South, your enemy
territory will be right across that river.

18
00:06:53,496 --> 00:06:59,751
Well, sir, there is no great outcry
for secession in, uh, Virginia.

19
00:06:59,919 --> 00:07:05,006
lt's not a foregone conclusion that
Virginia or Tennessee or Arkansas...

20
00:07:05,174 --> 00:07:08,468
. ..or Kentucky will join the rebellion.

21
00:07:09,387 --> 00:07:13,056
My friend, may l humbly submit that
you're mistaken about Virginia.

22
00:07:13,224 --> 00:07:16,852
As you know, the legislature is
convening in Richmond this very day...

23
00:07:17,019 --> 00:07:20,105
. ..to discuss the very issue of secession.

24
00:07:20,273 --> 00:07:23,567
Now, perhaps you know their mind
better than they themselves.

25
00:07:26,612 --> 00:07:32,868
And l regret to say the president's
hasty calling up of 75,000 volunteers. . .

26
00:07:33,035 --> 00:07:36,204
. ..to subdue the rebellion
in the cotton states. . .

27
00:07:36,372 --> 00:07:41,251
. ..has done nothing to ameliorate
the crisis. lt has only deepened it.

28
00:07:43,212 --> 00:07:47,591
l trust you're not being
too hasty yourself, colonel.

29
00:07:47,758 --> 00:07:53,847
This is a great opportunity
for you to serve your country.

30
00:07:57,393 --> 00:07:59,728
My country, Mr. Blair?

31
00:08:01,606 --> 00:08:05,233
l never thought l'd see the day
the president of the United States. . .

32
00:08:05,401 --> 00:08:09,237
. ..would raise an army
to invade his own country.

33
00:08:12,533 --> 00:08:18,914
No, Mr. Blair, l cannot lead it.
l will not lead it. No.

34
00:08:21,792 --> 00:08:24,794
l'm sorry to hear you say that, sir.

35
00:08:24,962 --> 00:08:28,840
l fear you're making
a most dreadful mistake.

36
00:08:37,892 --> 00:08:43,021
Sir, please convey my deep sense of
honor and gratitude to the president...

37
00:08:43,189 --> 00:08:45,690
. ..but l must decline his offer.

38
00:08:46,025 --> 00:08:47,734
Please tell him.

39
00:08:48,528 --> 00:08:53,198
Please be clear. l have
never taken my duties lightly. . .

40
00:08:53,366 --> 00:08:59,579
. ..but l have no greater duty
than to my home, to Virginia.

41
00:09:08,381 --> 00:09:09,464
Thank you, sir.

42
00:09:09,715 --> 00:09:11,383
[SOLDlER SHOUTlNG lNDlSTlNCTLY]

43
00:09:24,105 --> 00:09:28,984
JACKSON: Gentlemen, if you are going
to succeed at this institution...

44
00:09:29,151 --> 00:09:32,821
. ..you have one common goal:
To learn your lessons.

45
00:09:33,155 --> 00:09:35,448
lf you are placing
your energies elsewhere...

46
00:09:35,616 --> 00:09:42,497
. ..you will not succeed either with me
or in your careers as military officers.

47
00:09:42,665 --> 00:09:46,668
l had hoped you'd see that with a
proper grasp of the artillery principles...

48
00:09:46,836 --> 00:09:49,838
. .. l've laid before you today,
you would learn to apply. . .

49
00:09:50,006 --> 00:09:53,800
. ..these principles with great
effectiveness in your field experiences.

50
00:09:53,968 --> 00:09:58,972
But since you seem unable
to grasp these principles...

51
00:09:59,140 --> 00:10:04,477
. .. l'm forced to conclude l must repeat
this lesson tomorrow, word for word.

52
00:10:07,481 --> 00:10:09,357
Word for word.

53
00:10:11,068 --> 00:10:12,360
[CROWD SHOUTlNG NEARBY]

54
00:10:17,450 --> 00:10:21,202
CROWD [CHANTlNG]:
Secession! Secession! Secession!

55
00:10:28,711 --> 00:10:30,712
Hoist it! Hoist it up!

56
00:10:36,927 --> 00:10:42,682
Major, listen to them.
The leaders of our intellectual future...

57
00:10:42,850 --> 00:10:45,435
. ..screaming for the destruction
of our nation!

58
00:10:45,603 --> 00:10:49,481
Sir, President Lincoln is raising
the troops.

59
00:10:52,193 --> 00:10:53,568
l ....

60
00:10:53,944 --> 00:11:00,116
l will not stay in a place where my
students dishonor their country's flag.

61
00:11:02,328 --> 00:11:07,415
Major, l'm leaving
for Pennsylvania tomorrow.

62
00:11:08,042 --> 00:11:11,044
War is the sum of all evils.

63
00:11:11,212 --> 00:11:14,589
But if l know myself,
all l am and all l have. ..

64
00:11:14,757 --> 00:11:18,468
. ..is at the service of my
home, my country.

65
00:11:18,636 --> 00:11:20,929
Your country, Thomas?

66
00:11:21,097 --> 00:11:25,392
Your country, my country. lt's all one.

67
00:11:26,394 --> 00:11:30,939
All one, Thomas. All one.

68
00:11:39,657 --> 00:11:45,328
So that in the midst of the searching
of souls and the gnashing of teeth. . .

69
00:11:45,496 --> 00:11:48,248
. ..the delegates of this convention...

70
00:11:48,416 --> 00:11:54,129
. ..harried by the actions of a belligerent
usurper and the radicals of his party. ..

71
00:11:54,296 --> 00:11:56,798
. ..have stumbled into secession.

72
00:11:56,966 --> 00:12:01,928
Now God knows, l and many
in this room have resisted it.

73
00:12:02,096 --> 00:12:07,726
But how could there be union
with a section of the country. . .

74
00:12:07,893 --> 00:12:12,522
. ..that wants to impose
its will through coercion?

75
00:12:12,690 --> 00:12:18,611
Now that Virginia confronts the armed
might of the United States. . .

76
00:12:18,779 --> 00:12:24,659
. ..we Virginians have determined
that not one spot of her sacred soil...

77
00:12:24,827 --> 00:12:28,621
. ..be polluted by the foot of an invader.

78
00:12:28,789 --> 00:12:30,206
[CROWD CHEERlNG]

79
00:12:36,505 --> 00:12:38,506
God bless Virginia!

80
00:12:41,010 --> 00:12:45,472
Now, in the memory of that great
Virginian, George Washington.. .

81
00:12:45,639 --> 00:12:49,851
. ..who was first in the hearts
of his countrymen and calling also. . .

82
00:12:50,019 --> 00:12:55,982
. ..upon the memory of his own gallant
father, General Light-Horse Harry Lee. . .

83
00:12:56,233 --> 00:13:02,071
. ..this convention now calls upon
Robert Edward Lee to take command. . .

84
00:13:02,239 --> 00:13:06,618
. ..of the armed forces of
the Citizen Army of Virginia.

85
00:13:06,786 --> 00:13:08,369
[CROWD CHEERlNG]

86
00:13:36,440 --> 00:13:40,235
Mr. President, gentlemen
of the convention...

87
00:13:40,402 --> 00:13:44,614
. .. l'm profoundly impressed
by the solemnity of the occasion...

88
00:13:44,782 --> 00:13:48,076
. ..for which l must say
l was not prepared.

89
00:13:48,744 --> 00:13:53,081
l accept the position assigned me
by your partiality.

90
00:13:54,041 --> 00:13:59,087
l would have much preferred had
your choice fallen on an abler man.

91
00:14:00,089 --> 00:14:05,301
But trusting to Almighty God,
an approving conscience...

92
00:14:05,469 --> 00:14:08,263
. ..and the aid of my fellow citizens...

93
00:14:08,931 --> 00:14:13,101
. .. l devote myself to the service
of my native state. . .

94
00:14:14,103 --> 00:14:20,567
. ..in whose behalf alone will l
ever again draw my sword.

95
00:14:20,734 --> 00:14:22,151
[CROWD CHEERlNG]

96
00:14:43,215 --> 00:14:44,465
[PLAYlNG PlANO]

97
00:15:54,203 --> 00:16:00,500
We must not fear the final result of this
war, but many a loved one will fall...

98
00:16:01,043 --> 00:16:03,795
. ..and many a heart throb
with anguish. . .

99
00:16:03,963 --> 00:16:08,299
. ..before we can breathe the exhilarating
atmosphere of freedom. . .

100
00:16:08,467 --> 00:16:13,972
. ..and feel the sweet assurance
of safety and peace once more.

101
00:16:14,807 --> 00:16:19,060
There's nothing in this life more dear
to me than my children...

102
00:16:19,311 --> 00:16:22,814
. ..except perhaps the memory
of your wonderful father.

103
00:16:26,235 --> 00:16:30,947
When you go to Richmond,
and wherever this war takes you. . .

104
00:16:31,281 --> 00:16:37,787
. ..you must not fear for us.
We will be with you wherever you go.

105
00:16:38,831 --> 00:16:44,252
Surely goodness and mercy have
followed me all the days of my life.

106
00:16:51,427 --> 00:16:57,306
Now be on your way,
and God be with you.

107
00:17:03,522 --> 00:17:06,315
Y'all be coming on back, you hear?

108
00:17:07,901 --> 00:17:09,861
We'll be back, Martha.

109
00:17:16,660 --> 00:17:18,327
[MARCHlNG BAND
PLAYlNG UPBEAT MUSlC]

110
00:17:34,303 --> 00:17:36,804
Mr. Wilkes, sir.

111
00:17:38,223 --> 00:17:41,350
Would you be kind enough
as to autograph my playbill?

112
00:17:44,772 --> 00:17:46,814
l was never much interested
in Shakespeare. ..

113
00:17:46,982 --> 00:17:51,194
-Mm-hm.
-. . .until l saw you play Richard l l l.

114
00:17:51,361 --> 00:17:56,491
"A horse! A horse!
My kingdom for a horse!"

115
00:17:57,493 --> 00:18:01,162
Was ever woman in this humor wooed?

116
00:18:01,872 --> 00:18:04,832
Was ever woman in this humor won?

117
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:06,125
[CHUCKLES]

118
00:18:20,099 --> 00:18:22,391
Say, uh, haven't l seen you someplace?

119
00:18:22,559 --> 00:18:23,768
WOMAN:
Why, of course you have.

120
00:18:23,936 --> 00:18:28,523
This here is Mr. Wilkes Booth,
the finest actor in all of Richmond.

121
00:18:39,076 --> 00:18:41,035
All the world's a stage...

122
00:18:41,829 --> 00:18:45,123
. ..and we but its poor players.

123
00:18:45,749 --> 00:18:50,253
What better role than a soldier's
in defense of his home...

124
00:18:50,796 --> 00:18:52,171
. ..his honor.. .

125
00:18:53,465 --> 00:18:54,966
. ..and his beloved?

126
00:18:55,551 --> 00:18:56,759
[CROWD CHEERlNG]

127
00:19:07,646 --> 00:19:11,399
Good morning, major.
This just arrived for you.

128
00:19:31,295 --> 00:19:35,464
Cadet Norris, return to the lnstitute.
My compliments to Colonel Smith.

129
00:19:35,632 --> 00:19:38,426
l will be at his office
within the half-hour.

130
00:19:38,594 --> 00:19:39,886
Sir.

131
00:19:42,931 --> 00:19:47,185
"You are ordered to report with the
corps of cadets to camp instruction...

132
00:19:47,352 --> 00:19:50,438
. ..to begin training and organization
of the Provisional Army...

133
00:19:50,606 --> 00:19:53,524
. ..for the defense of the
Commonwealth of Virginia."

134
00:19:55,402 --> 00:19:57,445
My esposita.

135
00:19:59,323 --> 00:20:02,200
Come, before l leave, we must sit...

136
00:20:02,367 --> 00:20:05,870
. ..read together, the verse.

137
00:20:09,124 --> 00:20:10,583
Here.

138
00:20:12,211 --> 00:20:17,632
Yes, here. Corinthians--
Second Corinthians, chapter five.

139
00:20:18,300 --> 00:20:21,469
l have been thinking about this verse.

140
00:20:22,763 --> 00:20:28,809
"For we know that if our earthly house
of this Tabernacle were dissolved...

141
00:20:28,977 --> 00:20:31,646
. ..we have a building of God.

142
00:20:31,813 --> 00:20:37,151
A house not made with hands,
eternal in the heavens."

143
00:20:44,451 --> 00:20:46,494
O, Almighty God. . .

144
00:20:47,537 --> 00:20:51,040
. ..grant that if it be thy will...

145
00:20:51,208 --> 00:20:55,461
. ..thou wilt still avert the threatening
danger and bring us peace.

146
00:20:58,507 --> 00:21:01,759
Keep her whom l love in
thy protected care.

147
00:21:03,512 --> 00:21:08,015
And bring us all at last to
the joy of thy eternal kingdom.

148
00:21:09,351 --> 00:21:10,851
[MARCHlNG BAND PLAYlNG
UPBEAT MUSlC]

149
00:21:11,019 --> 00:21:12,103
[CROWD CHEERlNG]

150
00:21:28,203 --> 00:21:29,245
MAN 1 :
Give them hell, sir!

151
00:21:38,422 --> 00:21:40,131
MAN 2:
Yeah, give them hell, men!

152
00:22:30,390 --> 00:22:35,770
PASTOR: "The Lord is my light.
My salvation. Whom shall l fear?

153
00:22:36,271 --> 00:22:42,193
The Lord is the strength in my life.
Of whom shall l be afraid?

154
00:22:42,361 --> 00:22:45,946
When the wicked, even mine
enemies and my foes...

155
00:22:46,114 --> 00:22:51,869
...came upon me to eat up my flesh,
they stumbled and fell.

156
00:22:52,120 --> 00:22:58,584
Though unhost should encamp against
me, my heart shall not fear.

157
00:22:58,960 --> 00:23:02,922
Though war should rise up against me.

158
00:23:03,090 --> 00:23:06,467
ln this will l be comforted."

159
00:24:06,653 --> 00:24:09,405
REVEREND JENKlNS:
Secession is inexcusable.

160
00:24:09,573 --> 00:24:12,992
Southerners and Northerners
can still work together.

161
00:24:13,910 --> 00:24:18,330
Slavery will eventually die
of natural causes.

162
00:24:18,498 --> 00:24:21,959
But the breakup of the Union
will inaugurate wars. . .

163
00:24:22,127 --> 00:24:25,212
. ..of a hundred generations in America...

164
00:24:25,380 --> 00:24:29,467
. ..only to repeat the bloody
history of Europe.

165
00:24:30,093 --> 00:24:33,846
lf Virginia adheres
to the United States, l adhere.

166
00:24:34,014 --> 00:24:40,352
Her determination must control mine.
This is my understanding of patriotism.

167
00:24:40,520 --> 00:24:45,357
And though l love the Union,
l love Virginia more.

168
00:24:48,069 --> 00:24:53,365
Private Jenkins, because of the high
regard with which l hold your father...

169
00:24:53,533 --> 00:24:58,746
. ..you are free to do as you please. You may
return to his new home in Pennsylvania.

170
00:24:58,914 --> 00:25:05,002
lt is your decision.
But, if you decide to stay with us.. .

171
00:25:05,962 --> 00:25:11,467
. ..you may never again leave. lf you do,
you'll be treated as a deserter.

172
00:25:23,438 --> 00:25:27,525
Colonel Jackson, sir. Father.

173
00:25:29,945 --> 00:25:32,947
l am a soldier in the 4th Virginia.

174
00:25:34,199 --> 00:25:37,326
And in the 4th Virginia l will stay.

175
00:25:38,995 --> 00:25:41,163
And if needs be, die.

176
00:25:47,963 --> 00:25:52,341
-Then l will take my leave.
-No, sir.

177
00:25:54,302 --> 00:25:58,514
lt is l who will leave the two of you to
have some time together on your own.

178
00:25:58,682 --> 00:26:01,308
You may have this room
for as long as you require it.

179
00:26:01,476 --> 00:26:03,102
Thank you.

180
00:26:05,730 --> 00:26:07,773
Farewell, colonel.

181
00:26:10,860 --> 00:26:15,573
May we meet again in happier times.

182
00:26:16,241 --> 00:26:21,161
And if not in this troubled world
may we meet in. . . .

183
00:26:23,498 --> 00:26:24,748
ln heaven.

184
00:26:28,044 --> 00:26:30,671
HARMAN:
This train was on its way to Washington.

185
00:26:30,839 --> 00:26:34,883
lts livestock's been requisitioned
by the Confederate government.

186
00:26:35,051 --> 00:26:38,679
There's enough damn beef in here
to keep us fed for quite a while.

187
00:26:38,847 --> 00:26:43,100
And as many steeds as would
damn well meet our current needs.

188
00:26:43,518 --> 00:26:48,188
With your permission, sir, we've made
a selection of the more promising horses.

189
00:26:48,356 --> 00:26:49,898
There's some damn fine ones here.

190
00:26:50,066 --> 00:26:53,527
JACKSON:
Mr. Harman, l fear you are a wicked man.

191
00:26:59,492 --> 00:27:02,745
-This animal looks fit for the duty.
-Then he's yours, sir.

192
00:27:06,249 --> 00:27:10,085
That small horse over there,
has he been assigned?

193
00:27:10,253 --> 00:27:14,048
Well, it's a well-rounded sorrel, sir,
but too small for you.

194
00:27:14,215 --> 00:27:16,258
You'll have your feet
dragging in the dust.

195
00:27:16,426 --> 00:27:18,218
l was thinking of my wife, Anna.

196
00:27:18,386 --> 00:27:20,220
He would make a fine present for her.

197
00:27:21,306 --> 00:27:24,808
HARMAN: Well, that it would, sir.
Shall l arrange for the purchase?

198
00:27:27,937 --> 00:27:30,147
Leave the bill of the sale
at my headquarters.

199
00:27:30,899 --> 00:27:32,483
l will buy them both.

200
00:27:32,651 --> 00:27:35,069
The Confederate Treasury is honored, sir.

201
00:27:35,236 --> 00:27:37,446
And may you both sit well in the saddle.

202
00:27:37,614 --> 00:27:39,323
What shall l call you?

203
00:27:46,331 --> 00:27:48,582
-Good morning, sir.
-Reverend Pendleton.

204
00:27:48,750 --> 00:27:52,878
-How goes it with the artillery today?
-You're just in time for a christening.

205
00:27:53,046 --> 00:27:58,634
The men have decided to name the
howitzers: Matthew, Mark, Luke and John.

206
00:27:58,927 --> 00:28:04,098
l'm sure your men will spread the gospel
wherever they encounter the enemy.

207
00:28:04,265 --> 00:28:06,475
Has my son proven a worthy adjutant?

208
00:28:06,935 --> 00:28:11,605
l'm certain Captain Pendleton will prove
himself deserving of the family name.

209
00:28:15,777 --> 00:28:21,115
ALL:
Break! Guard! Charge!

210
00:28:29,749 --> 00:28:33,293
As if you could ever get close enough
to stick a man with this.

211
00:28:33,461 --> 00:28:36,964
You can give me your bayonet
if you have no further use for it.

212
00:28:37,132 --> 00:28:38,966
What you gonna do with two of them?

213
00:28:39,759 --> 00:28:42,136
You never heard of spare parts?

214
00:28:42,971 --> 00:28:46,682
Pogue, your only hope is that some Yank
puts you out of your misery.

215
00:28:50,395 --> 00:28:51,979
Captain White.

216
00:28:52,147 --> 00:28:54,398
How fare the scholars
of Washington College?

217
00:28:54,566 --> 00:28:57,317
Are they making their transition
from books to bullets?

218
00:28:57,485 --> 00:29:01,905
A few more days of drill, and my boys
will surpass the cadets of VMl .

219
00:29:02,073 --> 00:29:06,034
Drill, Professor White, drill and drill.
Remember Alexander in Anatolia.

220
00:29:06,202 --> 00:29:09,747
Caesar in Gaul. Napoleon in lberia.

221
00:29:09,914 --> 00:29:13,625
We march by day,
and read Xenophon by night.

222
00:29:13,793 --> 00:29:18,213
-We will be your Greek phalanx.
-Then you must begin with the bayonet.

223
00:29:18,381 --> 00:29:22,342
The bayonet must be for a Virginian
what the sarissa was for a Macedonian.

224
00:29:22,510 --> 00:29:26,680
lf the Yankees dare set foot in Virginia,
we must show them the bayonet.

225
00:29:26,848 --> 00:29:30,184
Train with the bayonet
and we shall keep our freedom.

226
00:29:30,351 --> 00:29:31,935
WHlTE:
Yes, sir.

227
00:29:43,823 --> 00:29:45,199
Sir.

228
00:29:46,159 --> 00:29:51,038
Harman has a detachment ready to take
your sorrel to Mrs. Jackson in Lexington.

229
00:29:51,206 --> 00:29:53,457
The horse you chose
is waiting at headquarters.

230
00:29:53,625 --> 00:29:56,543
l've decided to keep
this little sorrel for myself.

231
00:29:56,711 --> 00:29:59,004
l prefer his gait
to that of the larger horse.

232
00:29:59,172 --> 00:30:02,883
Unlike the other, he has an even temper.

233
00:30:03,051 --> 00:30:07,095
He will need it where we are going.
Yes, l will keep it.

234
00:30:07,263 --> 00:30:09,973
And Mrs. Jackson?
What should we send her, sir?

235
00:30:10,141 --> 00:30:12,142
lnstruct Harman
to make another selection.

236
00:30:12,310 --> 00:30:16,730
My complete admiration in his choice
of livestock, if not in his choice of words.

237
00:30:16,898 --> 00:30:19,358
The man's vocabulary
is extremely repulsive.

238
00:30:19,526 --> 00:30:21,151
Yes, sir.

239
00:30:22,695 --> 00:30:25,239
-Will that be all, sir?
-Language is blasphemous...

240
00:30:25,406 --> 00:30:30,118
. ..but he is a good quartermaster,
a good quartermaster. You understand me?

241
00:30:30,286 --> 00:30:32,287
-Yes, sir.
-That's all.

242
00:30:36,042 --> 00:30:37,251
Hyah!

243
00:31:02,318 --> 00:31:05,946
SOLDlER 1 :
Blue, gray, green, even red uniforms.

244
00:31:06,114 --> 00:31:08,198
How are we to know who the enemy is?

245
00:31:08,366 --> 00:31:13,120
SOLDlER 2: You dang fool, you just shoot
at the man that's shooting at you!

246
00:31:14,956 --> 00:31:17,291
l thought we was gonna be trained.

247
00:31:17,458 --> 00:31:20,419
l could have done this walking
on my own back in Staunton.

248
00:31:20,587 --> 00:31:25,841
l never seen you walk in your life when
you didn't have to. Nor me, neither.

249
00:31:26,009 --> 00:31:28,594
What man in his senses
would cross his street...

250
00:31:28,761 --> 00:31:31,805
. ..when he could just be
sitting on his front porch?

251
00:31:31,973 --> 00:31:37,644
l done more walking this week than in
my life and my daddy's life put together.

252
00:31:37,937 --> 00:31:42,482
Who'll give us fresh shoes when these
are but tatters and old bits of laces?

253
00:31:48,573 --> 00:31:50,782
You'll excuse me, gentlemen.

254
00:31:59,626 --> 00:32:02,044
Lieutenant Colonel Stuart
reporting for duty.

255
00:32:02,211 --> 00:32:03,754
Colonel Stuart.

256
00:32:04,380 --> 00:32:07,966
-That's an impeccable hat, sir.
-Thank you, sir.

257
00:32:08,801 --> 00:32:14,598
-Colonel Stuart. You use tobacco?
-No, sir. Not in any form.

258
00:32:14,766 --> 00:32:19,019
Neither do l. l find l like it too much.

259
00:32:19,187 --> 00:32:20,896
Sit down.

260
00:32:22,565 --> 00:32:26,234
l understand from your record that
you are West Point, class of '54.

261
00:32:26,402 --> 00:32:28,612
Served since in the cavalry,
Ft. Clark, Texas.

262
00:32:29,030 --> 00:32:30,864
Operations against Apache, Comanche.

263
00:32:31,866 --> 00:32:34,117
Fought with Longstreet and Ewell, sir.

264
00:32:34,869 --> 00:32:38,497
Nasty business. Merciless climate.

265
00:32:39,707 --> 00:32:41,041
Glad to be home, sir.

266
00:32:42,293 --> 00:32:46,088
The Apache were defending their
homes, as we will be defending ours.

267
00:32:46,422 --> 00:32:51,051
lf we fight as well as the Apache,
l pity the Yankee invader.

268
00:32:51,219 --> 00:32:56,682
Colonel Stuart, if l had my way,
we would show no quarter to the enemy.

269
00:32:56,849 --> 00:33:01,311
No more than the redskins showed your
troopers. The black flag, sir.

270
00:33:01,688 --> 00:33:05,732
lf the North triumphs, it is not alone
the destruction of our property.

271
00:33:05,900 --> 00:33:08,318
lt is the prelude to anarchy, infidelity...

272
00:33:08,486 --> 00:33:11,279
. ..the loss of free
and responsible government.

273
00:33:11,447 --> 00:33:15,367
lt is the triumph of commerce.
The banks, factories.

274
00:33:15,535 --> 00:33:18,578
We should meet the invader on
the verge of just defense...

275
00:33:18,746 --> 00:33:23,750
. ..and raise the black flag. No quarter to
the violators of our homes and firesides.

276
00:33:25,753 --> 00:33:29,965
Our political leadership is too timid
to face the reality of this coming war.

277
00:33:30,133 --> 00:33:34,344
They should look to the Bible.
lt is full of such wars.

278
00:33:34,512 --> 00:33:39,266
Only the black flag will bring the North
to its senses and rapidly end the war.

279
00:33:40,935 --> 00:33:42,310
Well, colonel.

280
00:33:43,271 --> 00:33:48,442
One way or the other, the South
will give them a warm reception.

281
00:33:48,609 --> 00:33:52,195
You'll be in charge of the cavalry
in the Harper's Ferry district.

282
00:33:52,363 --> 00:33:56,825
Your experience and your zeal
will be invaluable.

283
00:33:57,285 --> 00:33:59,161
Thank you, sir.

284
00:34:03,958 --> 00:34:05,375
And, colonel...

285
00:34:06,044 --> 00:34:11,089
. ..know that l will tell my men always
to gallop toward the enemy. . .

286
00:34:11,257 --> 00:34:13,050
. ..but trot away.

287
00:34:17,138 --> 00:34:18,722
"Trot."

288
00:34:22,435 --> 00:34:23,810
[CHATTERlNG]

289
00:34:25,396 --> 00:34:29,274
The ratification vote for secession is in.

290
00:34:29,442 --> 00:34:34,196
Reporting from all the counties
of Virginia, the vote is 4-to-1 in favor.

291
00:34:34,363 --> 00:34:35,739
[CROWD CHEERlNG]

292
00:34:39,202 --> 00:34:43,455
And l'm proud to report that the vote
in the Shenandoah Valley. . .

293
00:34:43,623 --> 00:34:47,834
. ..is 31 30 in favor, 1 0 against!

294
00:34:48,002 --> 00:34:49,419
[CROWD CHEERlNG]

295
00:34:50,213 --> 00:34:55,550
ln my own Rockbridge County, only one
person voted against leaving the Union.

296
00:34:55,718 --> 00:34:57,135
MAN:
Probably the village idiot!

297
00:34:57,303 --> 00:34:58,678
[ALL LAUGHlNG]

298
00:35:08,856 --> 00:35:10,315
SOLDlER 1 :
Order!

299
00:35:14,529 --> 00:35:18,365
-Parade, rest!
-Parade.

300
00:35:20,076 --> 00:35:21,660
Men of the valley.

301
00:35:26,582 --> 00:35:28,667
Citizen soldiers.

302
00:35:30,044 --> 00:35:34,881
l am here at the order of General Robert
E. Lee, commanding all Virginia forces.

303
00:35:36,884 --> 00:35:40,262
On April 1 5 of this year
of our Lord, 1 861 ...

304
00:35:40,429 --> 00:35:44,307
. ..Simon Cameron, the secretary of war
of the United States. . .

305
00:35:44,475 --> 00:35:49,062
. ..sent a telegram to our governor to
raise three regiments of infantry. ..

306
00:35:49,230 --> 00:35:53,066
. ..to be sent to assist in suppressing
the Southern Confederacy.

307
00:35:53,234 --> 00:35:57,904
Governor Letcher's answer is well
known to you, but perhaps not his words.

308
00:35:58,447 --> 00:36:01,241
His wire to Washington stated:

309
00:36:02,076 --> 00:36:05,412
"You have chosen to inaugurate civil war.

310
00:36:06,205 --> 00:36:09,166
Having done so, we will meet you
in a spirit as determined. . .

311
00:36:09,333 --> 00:36:13,795
. ..as the Lincoln administration
has exhibited toward the South."

312
00:36:14,672 --> 00:36:19,759
Two days later the Virginia legislature
were voting for secession.

313
00:36:21,596 --> 00:36:26,516
Just as we would not send any of our
soldiers to march in other states...

314
00:36:26,684 --> 00:36:29,102
. ..and tyrannize other people. ..

315
00:36:30,021 --> 00:36:34,524
. ..so will we never allow the armies
of others to march into our state.. .

316
00:36:34,692 --> 00:36:36,693
. ..and tyrannize our people.

317
00:36:37,278 --> 00:36:42,490
Like many of you, indeed most of you,
l've always been a Union man.

318
00:36:44,035 --> 00:36:48,955
lt is not with joy or with a light heart
that many have welcomed secession.

319
00:36:49,123 --> 00:36:53,001
Had our neighbors to the North practiced
a less bellicose form of persuasion. ..

320
00:36:53,169 --> 00:36:59,216
. ..this day might not have come.
But that day has been thrust upon us...

321
00:36:59,967 --> 00:37:03,595
. ..like it was thrust upon our ancestors.

322
00:37:04,305 --> 00:37:09,309
The Lincoln administration required
us to raise three regiments.

323
00:37:10,937 --> 00:37:13,396
Tell them we have done so.

324
00:37:45,221 --> 00:37:49,182
Soldiers! Commanding
General Johnston's orders:

325
00:37:50,184 --> 00:37:53,395
"General Beauregard is being attacked
at Manassas Junction...

326
00:37:53,562 --> 00:37:55,355
. ..by overwhelming forces."

327
00:37:55,982 --> 00:37:59,442
We have been ordered to cross
the Blue Ridge to his assistance.

328
00:37:59,694 --> 00:38:01,653
Every moment now is precious. ..

329
00:38:01,821 --> 00:38:06,658
. ..and the general hopes his soldiers
will step out and keep closed ranks.

330
00:38:06,826 --> 00:38:11,454
Well, this march is a forced march
to save our country.

331
00:38:11,622 --> 00:38:12,747
[CROWD CHEERlNG]

332
00:38:47,575 --> 00:38:51,286
You must get some rest, sir.

333
00:38:51,579 --> 00:38:56,583
l'll rest easier when Pendleton and
the artillery make it up this mountain.

334
00:38:59,545 --> 00:39:04,215
They'll make better time tomorrow, sir.
lt'll all be downhill.

335
00:39:06,260 --> 00:39:09,429
You'll trust me to wait for the guns, sir?

336
00:39:14,143 --> 00:39:16,019
Dr. McGuire.

337
00:39:18,439 --> 00:39:23,860
You're an excellent practitioner,
and l believe l will take your prescription.

338
00:39:39,251 --> 00:39:40,418
[GRUNTS]

339
00:39:42,630 --> 00:39:48,635
SOLDlER 1 : No fires, no tents.
Just like l always dreamed it'd be.

340
00:39:48,803 --> 00:39:52,972
You suppose the Virginia legislature was
gonna buy you your own personal tent?

341
00:39:53,140 --> 00:39:55,225
That's fine for now.

342
00:39:55,393 --> 00:40:01,064
You'll be humming a different tune when
it's raining, you're all covered in frost...

343
00:40:01,232 --> 00:40:04,943
. ..or you need me to dig you
out of a snowdrift.

344
00:40:05,111 --> 00:40:08,321
So damn dark the bats
run into each other.

345
00:40:08,489 --> 00:40:11,324
Old Hickory's just getting us
fit for the fighting.

346
00:40:11,492 --> 00:40:14,828
Old Hickory, Old Jack, Old Blue Light.

347
00:40:14,995 --> 00:40:18,373
How many names you got
for the old man, anyway?

348
00:40:19,291 --> 00:40:22,001
Them VMl boys come up
with the choice one.

349
00:40:22,169 --> 00:40:25,338
They calls him "Tom Fool" when
he's looking the other way.

350
00:40:25,756 --> 00:40:28,800
l'll be a fool if l listened
to you all livelong night.

351
00:40:30,344 --> 00:40:36,474
SOLDlER 2: Old Tom Fool. That name
ought to stick to him like a tick on a mule.

352
00:40:39,979 --> 00:40:45,024
That's it! Step lively! Two at a time!

353
00:40:45,192 --> 00:40:50,572
As quick as you can.
No dilly, no dally.

354
00:40:50,739 --> 00:40:57,203
One foot forward, then the other.
Nothing pretty, nothing fancy.

355
00:40:57,371 --> 00:41:03,877
lnto the train. Do it lovely,
do it ugly, all the same to me.

356
00:41:04,336 --> 00:41:07,547
-Colonel Jackson.
-Colonel Trimble.

357
00:41:07,715 --> 00:41:11,176
-l understand you're a train man.
-Baltimore and Ohio.

358
00:41:11,343 --> 00:41:15,472
Spent most of my life building lines,
and the past six months tearing them up.

359
00:41:15,806 --> 00:41:18,933
No use in leaving them in fine
fettle with a meddling Yankee.

360
00:41:19,268 --> 00:41:20,894
lf you'll excuse me, sir.

361
00:41:21,061 --> 00:41:25,231
Got to move these men where they'll
do the most damage to the enemy.

362
00:41:29,195 --> 00:41:30,904
Excuse me, ladies.

363
00:41:31,071 --> 00:41:34,574
Now that's the finest dressed man
in the whole Confederate Army.

364
00:41:34,825 --> 00:41:38,369
TRlMBLE:
ln you go! Up and over!

365
00:41:38,537 --> 00:41:41,289
Through the brush and in the clover.

366
00:41:41,457 --> 00:41:45,251
Crowd on in. Move it over.

367
00:42:05,439 --> 00:42:06,648
[GUNFlRE NEARBY]

368
00:42:41,350 --> 00:42:42,642
[SOLDlER SPEAKlNG lNDlSTlNCTLY]

369
00:42:57,241 --> 00:43:00,326
PENDLETON:
That's General Bee's brigade!

370
00:43:09,295 --> 00:43:12,088
lnform General Bee the
1 st Virginians are on the field.

371
00:43:12,298 --> 00:43:14,924
Ask him, can he hold long enough
for me to deploy my men?

372
00:43:15,092 --> 00:43:16,759
Yes, sir! l'll ask him!

373
00:43:16,927 --> 00:43:20,013
They may not hold, gentlemen.
We must assume they cannot.

374
00:43:20,180 --> 00:43:21,681
-Mr. Smith.
-Sir?

375
00:43:21,849 --> 00:43:26,102
lnstruct lmboden and Stanard to position
their batteries in the center of the crest.

376
00:43:26,312 --> 00:43:29,522
l want the 4th and the 27th
regiments stationed as support.

377
00:43:29,690 --> 00:43:31,608
l want the 5th Regiment
posted to their right. . .

378
00:43:31,775 --> 00:43:33,568
. ..the 2nd and 33rd to the left.
Understood?

379
00:43:33,736 --> 00:43:34,777
-Yes, sir.
-Mm-hm.

380
00:43:35,487 --> 00:43:36,738
[SOLDlERS SHOUTlNG]

381
00:43:46,540 --> 00:43:49,208
Counter battery fire!

382
00:43:49,376 --> 00:43:51,377
Eight hundred yards!

383
00:43:51,545 --> 00:43:55,715
-Shell! Five-second fuse!
-Fire!

384
00:44:04,558 --> 00:44:09,479
Counter battery fire. Eight hundred yards.

385
00:44:09,647 --> 00:44:13,733
Shell, five inch. Five-second fuse.

386
00:44:13,901 --> 00:44:15,234
-Fire one!
-Two!

387
00:44:15,402 --> 00:44:17,403
-Three!
-Five, fire!

388
00:44:18,030 --> 00:44:19,572
Get primed!

389
00:44:19,740 --> 00:44:21,240
Fire!

390
00:44:24,578 --> 00:44:25,787
[SOLDlERS SCREAMlNG]

391
00:44:33,003 --> 00:44:37,799
General! Our line on Matthew's Hill
has broken. They are beating us back.

392
00:44:37,966 --> 00:44:40,426
Then we must give them the bayonet!

393
00:44:40,636 --> 00:44:45,890
1 st Brigade, move up to a position just
below the crest of the hill. And stay low!

394
00:44:46,058 --> 00:44:47,600
-Sir.
-Hyah!

395
00:44:53,941 --> 00:44:55,441
Rally, men! Rally!

396
00:44:57,236 --> 00:44:58,778
Look!

397
00:44:58,946 --> 00:45:02,115
There is Jackson, standing like a stone wall.

398
00:45:02,282 --> 00:45:05,201
Let us determine to die here today
and we will conquer.

399
00:45:05,411 --> 00:45:07,078
Rally behind the Virginians!

400
00:45:07,246 --> 00:45:09,080
[SOLDlERS CHEERlNG]

401
00:45:23,804 --> 00:45:25,972
Fix bayonets.

402
00:45:26,140 --> 00:45:27,932
-Fix bayonets!
-Fix!

403
00:45:35,816 --> 00:45:37,275
SOLDlER:
Fire!

404
00:45:54,918 --> 00:45:56,836
Fill in there--!

405
00:46:02,885 --> 00:46:05,344
lnstruct the men to lay down!
Hug the ground!

406
00:46:05,554 --> 00:46:10,016
-Lie down, men!
-Privates! First rank, lie down!

407
00:46:10,184 --> 00:46:13,603
Second rank, kneel!

408
00:46:32,122 --> 00:46:34,457
They are coming, boys.

409
00:46:34,750 --> 00:46:38,211
Wait till they get close before you shoot.

410
00:46:42,216 --> 00:46:43,382
Hold your lines!

411
00:46:45,052 --> 00:46:46,260
[SCREAMlNG]

412
00:46:47,888 --> 00:46:49,889
Halt!

413
00:46:52,851 --> 00:46:55,478
Hold your fire!

414
00:46:55,687 --> 00:46:57,396
Ready!

415
00:46:57,606 --> 00:46:59,565
Aim!

416
00:47:00,359 --> 00:47:06,572
Fire!

417
00:47:06,949 --> 00:47:08,157
[SHOUTS]

418
00:47:08,742 --> 00:47:10,451
Fire! Reload!

419
00:47:10,619 --> 00:47:12,912
SOLDlER 1 : Rise up!
SOLDlER 2: Quickly, boys!

420
00:47:13,747 --> 00:47:14,831
Rise up!

421
00:47:18,252 --> 00:47:19,961
Quickly, men! Quickly!

422
00:47:21,839 --> 00:47:23,714
Ready!

423
00:47:24,466 --> 00:47:26,175
Aim!

424
00:47:27,928 --> 00:47:36,269
Fire!

425
00:47:40,274 --> 00:47:43,442
Reload! Reload, men!

426
00:47:44,444 --> 00:47:46,988
Come on, boys!
Quick and we can whip them!

427
00:47:47,197 --> 00:47:50,992
-Easy, men. We have no orders to advance!
-Get back in the ranks!

428
00:47:51,535 --> 00:47:54,871
Steady, men. Steady!

429
00:47:57,082 --> 00:47:58,332
Damn it.

430
00:47:58,500 --> 00:48:01,168
Charge!

431
00:48:06,884 --> 00:48:08,134
lt's Cummings' boys.

432
00:48:10,888 --> 00:48:13,306
-What are they doing?
-Easy, Mr. Pendleton. Easy.

433
00:48:13,473 --> 00:48:16,183
Good to have your dander up,
but discipline wins the day.

434
00:48:41,752 --> 00:48:45,880
SOLDlER: About-face! About-face, men!
Aim! Fire!

435
00:48:47,049 --> 00:48:50,134
For God's sakes, forward!

436
00:49:02,064 --> 00:49:05,358
General, sir, the day is going against us.

437
00:49:06,193 --> 00:49:10,404
lf you think so, sir, you had better
not say anything about it.

438
00:49:29,508 --> 00:49:31,425
Rise up, rise up!

439
00:49:31,885 --> 00:49:34,011
Rise up, Virginia!

440
00:49:34,179 --> 00:49:39,100
Stand up, you men! Stand up, you free men!
We're gonna charge them.

441
00:49:39,309 --> 00:49:43,062
We're gonna drive them to Washington!
Stand up, Virginia!

442
00:49:45,691 --> 00:49:48,150
1 st Brigade...

443
00:49:48,318 --> 00:49:50,069
. ..reserve your fire...

444
00:49:50,237 --> 00:49:52,905
. ..till they come within 50 yards. . .

445
00:49:53,073 --> 00:49:55,408
. ..then fire!

446
00:49:55,575 --> 00:49:58,285
And give them the bayonet!

447
00:49:58,495 --> 00:50:01,038
And when you charge...

448
00:50:01,206 --> 00:50:02,915
. ..yell like Furies!

449
00:50:10,048 --> 00:50:14,093
-Ready! Aim!
-Aim!

450
00:50:16,263 --> 00:50:18,472
-Fire!
-Fire!

451
00:50:22,477 --> 00:50:25,771
Charge bayonets!

452
00:50:25,939 --> 00:50:27,398
[ALL SHOUTlNG]

453
00:50:53,884 --> 00:50:57,595
Charge!

454
00:51:17,866 --> 00:51:20,576
Press on! Press on!

455
00:51:52,859 --> 00:51:55,194
SOLDlER:
l surrender! l surrender!

456
00:52:17,008 --> 00:52:18,217
[SOLDlER PLAYlNG BUGLE]

457
00:53:20,113 --> 00:53:21,405
[THUNDER CRASHlNG]

458
00:54:10,997 --> 00:54:12,790
SMlTH:
General?

459
00:54:14,542 --> 00:54:18,879
How is it you can keep so serene. . .

460
00:54:19,547 --> 00:54:24,426
. ..and stay so utterly insensible...

461
00:54:25,345 --> 00:54:29,181
. ..with a storm of shells and bullets
raining about your head?

462
00:54:29,349 --> 00:54:31,767
Captain Smith...

463
00:54:31,935 --> 00:54:37,231
. ..my religious belief teaches me
to feel as safe in battle as in bed.

464
00:54:37,399 --> 00:54:41,860
God has fixed the time for my death,
l do not concern myself with that...

465
00:54:42,028 --> 00:54:45,698
. ..but to be always ready,
whenever it may overtake me.

466
00:54:46,533 --> 00:54:49,326
That is the way all men should live.

467
00:54:50,120 --> 00:54:52,538
Then all men would be equally brave.

468
00:55:05,468 --> 00:55:11,223
Preliminary reports for the brigade, sir.
One hundred and eleven dead.

469
00:55:11,433 --> 00:55:15,144
Three hundred seventy-three
wounded or missing.

470
00:55:15,312 --> 00:55:18,981
And if l may ask, sir, how's your hand?

471
00:55:19,149 --> 00:55:24,153
Just a spent bullet. No more than
a scratch really, Mr. Pendleton.

472
00:55:24,321 --> 00:55:29,074
l'm more than pleased with the part
performed by the brigade during the action.

473
00:55:29,576 --> 00:55:31,744
Through the blessing of God. . .

474
00:55:33,038 --> 00:55:37,583
. ..they met the thus far victorious enemy
and turned the fortunes of the day.

475
00:55:40,378 --> 00:55:42,588
Good evening, gentlemen.

476
00:55:43,089 --> 00:55:44,965
Tomorrow's a new day.

477
00:55:45,592 --> 00:55:47,301
-Evening, general.
-Evening, sir.

478
00:55:47,469 --> 00:55:49,428
JACKSON:
Oh, Mr. Pendleton?

479
00:55:49,596 --> 00:55:51,430
Thank you for the report.

480
00:55:54,517 --> 00:55:57,311
l will never forget these men.

481
00:56:14,954 --> 00:56:20,584
Which is it tonight, John?
Hamlet? Richard Ill? Or the Scottish play?

482
00:56:20,960 --> 00:56:22,669
The schedule's posted.

483
00:56:22,837 --> 00:56:25,798
l'm relieved to see
you've prepared for your role.

484
00:56:26,758 --> 00:56:32,513
l admit, my concentration has been impaired
by the distractions of this war.

485
00:56:32,680 --> 00:56:36,475
Mm.
Then think "winter of our discontent."

486
00:56:37,143 --> 00:56:39,478
And what a glorious summer it will be. . .

487
00:56:39,646 --> 00:56:42,731
. ..when the South is free
of these meddling Yankees.

488
00:56:51,324 --> 00:56:53,659
Sometimes when l'm up on that stage...

489
00:56:53,827 --> 00:56:57,871
. ..brandishing the prop sword
or threatening with the mock word...

490
00:56:58,498 --> 00:57:01,875
. .. l wonder if it's more farce
than tragedy.

491
00:57:02,043 --> 00:57:04,837
More posturing than art.

492
00:57:06,089 --> 00:57:07,756
Harrison.

493
00:57:08,925 --> 00:57:13,345
As we recite and declaim,
others march and die.

494
00:57:17,183 --> 00:57:18,517
Down in Mississippi. . .

495
00:57:18,685 --> 00:57:22,354
. ..when all the other boys went
hunting or fishing, l was reading books.. .

496
00:57:23,064 --> 00:57:26,066
. ..learning Shakespeare sonnets by heart.

497
00:57:27,193 --> 00:57:29,236
My daddy said art
was the hardest thing.

498
00:57:29,404 --> 00:57:31,989
That everything else seems
more important at the time. . .

499
00:57:32,532 --> 00:57:35,534
. ..but that we needed it more than air.

500
00:57:35,702 --> 00:57:37,369
More than food, even.

501
00:57:38,997 --> 00:57:41,665
So now it's politics instead of hunting.

502
00:57:43,209 --> 00:57:44,668
Same old thing.

503
00:57:45,712 --> 00:57:49,631
Gotta stay concentrated
on what really matters.

504
00:57:51,718 --> 00:57:53,886
Shakespeare matters.

505
00:57:58,808 --> 00:58:00,934
Acting matters.

506
00:58:18,119 --> 00:58:20,537
Gentlemen, new orders
from the War Department.

507
00:58:21,831 --> 00:58:26,919
The Confederate Army's been reorganized
into three districts.

508
00:58:27,253 --> 00:58:30,547
That of the Potomac will remain
under General Beauregard.

509
00:58:30,715 --> 00:58:33,258
The Aquia under General Holmes.

510
00:58:34,636 --> 00:58:39,264
Um, l've been promoted
to major general. . .

511
00:58:40,016 --> 00:58:43,685
. ..commanding all forces in and around
the Shenandoah Valley.

512
00:58:44,103 --> 00:58:49,149
The entire army together will now be known
as the Army of Northern Virginia.

513
00:58:50,610 --> 00:58:53,779
Although l am being transferred
to Winchester...

514
00:58:53,947 --> 00:58:57,449
. ..the brigade must remain here
at Centreville.

515
00:58:58,117 --> 00:58:59,785
Begging your pardon, sir. ..

516
00:58:59,953 --> 00:59:02,746
. ..but the men would prefer
remaining under your command.

517
00:59:03,289 --> 00:59:04,790
That's right, sir.

518
00:59:04,958 --> 00:59:08,126
Couldn't the entire brigade be transferred
with you to the Valley?

519
00:59:08,294 --> 00:59:13,006
Gentlemen, such a degree
of public respect, confidence...

520
00:59:13,174 --> 00:59:17,594
. ..as puts it in one's power to serve
his country must be accepted and prized.

521
00:59:17,929 --> 00:59:19,805
But apart from that. . .

522
00:59:20,098 --> 00:59:22,849
. ..promotion among men is only
a temptation and a trouble.

523
00:59:23,017 --> 00:59:26,812
Had this not come to me as an order,
l should instantly have declined it. . .

524
00:59:26,980 --> 00:59:30,399
. ..continued in command
of my brave old brigade.

525
00:59:31,025 --> 00:59:34,945
Sir, may we hope. ..

526
00:59:35,738 --> 00:59:39,449
. ..that a formal entreaty
to the authorities in Richmond. . .

527
00:59:39,617 --> 00:59:42,744
. ..may effect a transfer
of the entire brigade to the Valley?

528
00:59:42,912 --> 00:59:43,996
Hear, hear.

529
00:59:44,163 --> 00:59:47,332
l'll not stop you
from making such a request.

530
00:59:47,500 --> 00:59:51,169
But for now, we must prepare ourselves.

531
00:59:53,256 --> 00:59:56,174
We shall all have our labors to perform...

532
00:59:56,968 --> 01:00:02,347
. ..but with the help
of an ever-kindly heavenly father. . .

533
01:00:02,515 --> 01:00:05,809
. .. l trust he will enable us
to accomplish them.

534
01:00:07,228 --> 01:00:09,980
SOLDlER:
Forward!

535
01:00:10,148 --> 01:00:12,316
Rest!

536
01:00:18,323 --> 01:00:21,867
Throughout the broad extent
of the country...

537
01:00:22,035 --> 01:00:24,661
. ..through which you have marched. . .

538
01:00:25,872 --> 01:00:30,042
. ..by your respect for the rights
and property of others. ..

539
01:00:30,877 --> 01:00:34,421
. ..you have always shown you are soldiers,
not only to defend. . .

540
01:00:35,381 --> 01:00:39,176
. ..but able and willing
both to defend and protect.

541
01:00:39,344 --> 01:00:41,845
You've already won...

542
01:00:43,014 --> 01:00:46,850
. ..a brilliant reputation throughout the Army
of the whole Confederacy.

543
01:00:47,018 --> 01:00:50,562
And l trust in the future
by your deeds in the field...

544
01:00:51,898 --> 01:00:56,401
. ..and by the assistance of the same kind
providence who has favored our cause...

545
01:00:56,569 --> 01:01:02,240
. ..you will win more victories and add
luster to the reputation you now enjoy.

546
01:01:03,868 --> 01:01:07,412
You already gained a proud position. . .

547
01:01:07,872 --> 01:01:10,916
. ..in the future history of this. . .

548
01:01:11,084 --> 01:01:13,919
. ..our second war of independence.

549
01:01:17,590 --> 01:01:22,094
l shall look with anxiety
to your future movements...

550
01:01:22,553 --> 01:01:26,390
. ..and l trust whenever l shall hear
of the 1 st Brigade. . .

551
01:01:26,557 --> 01:01:28,725
. ..on the field of battle. . .

552
01:01:28,893 --> 01:01:34,606
. ..it will be of still nobler deeds achieved
and higher reputation won.

553
01:01:39,946 --> 01:01:45,409
ln the Army of the Shenandoah,
you were the 1 st Brigade.

554
01:01:45,910 --> 01:01:49,287
ln the Army of the Potomac,
you were the 1 st Brigade.

555
01:01:49,789 --> 01:01:53,959
ln the 2nd Corps of this Army,
you are the 1 st Brigade.

556
01:01:54,127 --> 01:01:58,714
You are the 1 st Brigade
in the affections of your general.

557
01:02:00,133 --> 01:02:04,845
And l hope by your future deeds and bearing
you will be handed down to posterity. . .

558
01:02:05,638 --> 01:02:08,098
. ..as the 1 st Brigade. . .

559
01:02:08,266 --> 01:02:11,727
. ..in this, our second war of independence.

560
01:02:17,734 --> 01:02:19,735
Farewell!

561
01:02:21,821 --> 01:02:23,196
[ALL CHEERlNG]

562
01:02:27,660 --> 01:02:31,913
SOLDlERS [CHANTlNG]:
Jackson! Jackson! Jackson! Jackson!

563
01:02:32,081 --> 01:02:35,041
Jackson! Jackson! Jackson!

564
01:02:41,716 --> 01:02:46,678
CHAMBERLAlN: The universe itself
is subject to rules, to law.

565
01:02:46,846 --> 01:02:50,849
The super-abounding life lavished
on this world of ours.. .

566
01:02:51,392 --> 01:02:53,351
. ..is proof. . .

567
01:02:53,519 --> 01:02:56,313
. ..that the play of infinite freedom.. .

568
01:02:56,481 --> 01:03:01,318
. ..is here to help work out
the will of infinite law.

569
01:03:01,486 --> 01:03:06,823
The nature of the universe demonstrates. . .

570
01:03:06,991 --> 01:03:11,328
. ..that freedom can only exist...

571
01:03:11,496 --> 01:03:13,622
. ..as part of law.

572
01:03:17,293 --> 01:03:19,377
STUDENT:
Pardon me, Professor Chamberlain. . .

573
01:03:19,545 --> 01:03:23,507
. ..but how does the study of philosophy
intersect with real life?

574
01:03:24,217 --> 01:03:28,428
lf freedom can only exist as a part of law. . .

575
01:03:28,596 --> 01:03:31,556
. ..how can we continue to tolerate slavery
protected by law?

576
01:03:47,198 --> 01:03:48,740
Lawrence, l know.

577
01:03:50,535 --> 01:03:51,576
How?

578
01:03:53,412 --> 01:03:57,249
l've noticed the way you've been looking
into the children's room each night.

579
01:04:14,308 --> 01:04:15,559
Blue.

580
01:04:15,726 --> 01:04:19,396
Why blue uniforms? lt should be red.

581
01:04:19,564 --> 01:04:24,234
-Like the English, the color of blood.
-Are you angry with me?

582
01:04:24,402 --> 01:04:26,111
Lawrence, my darling Lawrence.

583
01:04:26,779 --> 01:04:29,865
Do you remember when you were
thinking of being a missionary?

584
01:04:30,032 --> 01:04:32,951
And you wrote me saying
that you wished your little wife...

585
01:04:33,119 --> 01:04:36,288
. ..was willing for you to take
whatever course you thought best...

586
01:04:36,455 --> 01:04:39,791
. ..and was ready to help you
in it with all her heart?

587
01:04:39,959 --> 01:04:43,837
"Little wife."
How could l ever have called you that?

588
01:04:44,005 --> 01:04:46,464
Your spirit is vaster than oceans.

589
01:04:47,466 --> 01:04:49,968
Then you wrote back.

590
01:04:51,971 --> 01:04:55,515
And l have never forgotten
what you said.

591
01:04:56,350 --> 01:04:59,686
You said, "Well, dear, she is willing. . .

592
01:04:59,854 --> 01:05:05,150
. ..and she feels that you know better
about the matter than she does."

593
01:05:07,278 --> 01:05:09,321
But now. . .

594
01:05:09,739 --> 01:05:13,033
. .. l never think l know better than you.

595
01:05:14,619 --> 01:05:18,538
l couldn't bear for you to feel that you
must forever remain at a stand. . .

596
01:05:18,706 --> 01:05:20,498
. ..just because you're married.

597
01:05:20,666 --> 01:05:25,086
l always want to help you on
in your excelsior striving.

598
01:05:27,506 --> 01:05:33,511
But l had a dream about you, Lawrence.
Last night.

599
01:05:33,679 --> 01:05:37,515
While you were away,
offering your services to the governor.

600
01:05:39,268 --> 01:05:45,106
l saw you in my dream.
There were boys in blue marching past.

601
01:05:45,399 --> 01:05:50,028
Some of the boys that we know.

602
01:05:50,196 --> 01:05:53,198
And there you were. . .

603
01:05:53,366 --> 01:05:56,785
. ..riding ahead of them
on a great, white horse.

604
01:05:57,787 --> 01:06:02,540
Fanny, my love, l felt l had to go.

605
01:06:02,708 --> 01:06:06,753
l offered the governor my services,
wherever he wanted to place me.

606
01:06:07,046 --> 01:06:11,132
l thought he'd probably order me
to an officer.

607
01:06:11,300 --> 01:06:15,553
-Speeches, administration.
-Oh.

608
01:06:15,721 --> 01:06:17,347
Lawrence...

609
01:06:17,515 --> 01:06:20,809
. .. l know you.
When you do a thing, you do it à l'outrance.

610
01:06:22,144 --> 01:06:26,815
-So? He gave you a commission, didn't he?
-They need serving officers.

611
01:06:35,866 --> 01:06:38,493
Five new regiments are being formed now.

612
01:06:38,995 --> 01:06:43,081
Maine has already sent 1 5.
How could l refuse?

613
01:06:43,249 --> 01:06:45,917
Poor Lawrence, damn you,
you'll be good at it too.

614
01:06:46,585 --> 01:06:50,630
You'll be good at soldiering just like
you're good at everything else. So go.

615
01:06:50,840 --> 01:06:52,841
Go do your duty to your country's flag...

616
01:06:53,009 --> 01:06:56,761
. ..go on and get your medals for bravery,
go and get yourself killed.

617
01:07:24,665 --> 01:07:26,332
That poem of Lovelace.

618
01:07:29,462 --> 01:07:35,967
That beautiful, horrible, damnable,
lovely, sad poem.

619
01:07:36,135 --> 01:07:39,304
l think that you recited it in my dream.

620
01:07:40,931 --> 01:07:43,641
Lovelace. "Off to the English Civil War"?

621
01:07:47,438 --> 01:07:50,857
l would not dare presume
to quote it now.

622
01:08:00,659 --> 01:08:05,747
Tell me not, sweet, l am unkind

623
01:08:06,832 --> 01:08:11,086
That from the nunnery
Of thy chaste breast and quiet mind

624
01:08:11,253 --> 01:08:13,588
To warlike arms l fly.

625
01:08:14,882 --> 01:08:18,802
True, a new mistress now l serve

626
01:08:18,969 --> 01:08:21,763
The first foe in the field

627
01:08:21,931 --> 01:08:28,019
And with a sterner faith embrace
The sword, a horse, a shield.

628
01:08:32,691 --> 01:08:36,194
Yet this inconstancy is such

629
01:08:36,362 --> 01:08:39,572
As thou too shalt adore.

630
01:08:41,492 --> 01:08:47,997
l could not love thee, dear, so much

631
01:08:50,417 --> 01:08:53,545
Loved l not honor more.

632
01:09:04,890 --> 01:09:07,559
You will be wounded.

633
01:09:09,520 --> 01:09:13,064
You will be changed by the horrors of it.

634
01:09:13,732 --> 01:09:16,151
But you will come home.

635
01:09:16,402 --> 01:09:20,697
l believe that, my love.
You will come home.

636
01:09:32,126 --> 01:09:33,751
[CLEARS THROAT]

637
01:09:34,420 --> 01:09:36,254
Come in.

638
01:09:38,007 --> 01:09:40,758
You must be Mr. Lewis.

639
01:09:41,177 --> 01:09:44,637
Ha, ha.
There's some that calls me Uncle Jim.

640
01:09:44,847 --> 01:09:48,933
Some calls me Big Jim.
Some folks just calls me Jim.

641
01:09:49,143 --> 01:09:52,687
l don't suppose you've heard
any of the names l get called?

642
01:09:52,855 --> 01:09:56,024
l heard Stonewall once.

643
01:09:56,192 --> 01:09:59,777
That name properly belongs
to the 1 st Virginia Brigade, not to me.

644
01:09:59,945 --> 01:10:03,781
-They were the ones who earned it.
-Some folks says otherwise.

645
01:10:03,949 --> 01:10:10,455
Folks say men can't fight without
nobody up front to lead them on.

646
01:10:10,623 --> 01:10:14,918
-l'm told you're a first-rate cook.
-Ha, ha. Yes, sir.

647
01:10:15,085 --> 01:10:19,214
They wasn't lying, told you that.
Whatever you likes to eat, l can cook it.

648
01:10:19,423 --> 01:10:23,635
Pan-fry, griddle, boil, bake. Roasted.

649
01:10:24,929 --> 01:10:29,307
And l understand you're from Lexington.
You come highly recommended to me, Jim.

650
01:10:30,226 --> 01:10:34,479
Lexington is my home, general.
Same as yours.

651
01:10:34,647 --> 01:10:38,191
lf l could do my share
in defending my home...

652
01:10:38,400 --> 01:10:40,652
. .. l'd be doing the same as you.

653
01:10:41,070 --> 01:10:44,822
l heard it was Napoleon hisself said:

654
01:10:44,990 --> 01:10:48,743
"An army can't march
but on its stomach."

655
01:10:52,581 --> 01:10:54,832
Well. . . .

656
01:10:55,000 --> 01:10:57,543
lf you love your country...

657
01:10:58,087 --> 01:11:00,129
. ..fear the Lord...

658
01:11:00,297 --> 01:11:04,592
. ..and have no trouble getting up at
4:00 in the morning, the job is yours.

659
01:11:08,347 --> 01:11:12,725
Yous got yourself a deal, general.

660
01:11:12,935 --> 01:11:15,311
Sir.

661
01:11:32,746 --> 01:11:35,873
My darling esposita.

662
01:11:39,878 --> 01:11:42,380
Welcome to Winchester.

663
01:11:42,548 --> 01:11:45,925
Thomas. Oh.

664
01:11:46,427 --> 01:11:49,637
-Come in out of the cold.
-Why, thank you.

665
01:12:00,149 --> 01:12:03,568
-l have been thinking, Thomas...
-Mm.

666
01:12:05,154 --> 01:12:06,738
. ..that it may have been a blessing. . .

667
01:12:06,905 --> 01:12:11,284
. ..that the Battle of Manassas
was fought on my birthday.

668
01:12:12,286 --> 01:12:14,412
Why is that?

669
01:12:15,205 --> 01:12:20,877
ln our old age, you will never forget it.

670
01:12:25,132 --> 01:12:30,011
l will forget my own
before l ever forget yours.

671
01:12:33,932 --> 01:12:35,808
[WHlSPERlNG]
Oh, Anna.

672
01:12:35,976 --> 01:12:37,852
Anna.

673
01:12:39,146 --> 01:12:41,731
[WHlSPERlNG]
What is it, Tom?

674
01:12:42,608 --> 01:12:44,442
What?

675
01:12:49,239 --> 01:12:55,661
Everything in this life seems so fragile.

676
01:12:56,288 --> 01:12:58,206
So temporary.

677
01:13:01,460 --> 01:13:05,630
[lN NORMAL VOlCE]
When we are separated, l fear...

678
01:13:05,798 --> 01:13:08,591
. .. l will never see you again.

679
01:13:10,260 --> 01:13:13,429
l fear we may never have a child.

680
01:13:16,058 --> 01:13:20,520
l fear l may lose you
if we dare to have a child.

681
01:13:20,687 --> 01:13:24,649
l know l should trust in the Lord. . .

682
01:13:25,484 --> 01:13:31,614
. ..but then l see the face
of my dear mama. . .

683
01:13:33,742 --> 01:13:38,621
. ..of my first wife, dead and cold.

684
01:13:39,081 --> 01:13:41,040
With our dead darling.

685
01:13:42,376 --> 01:13:46,838
Dead before he could draw
his first breath in this world.

686
01:13:48,257 --> 01:13:49,674
And l am afraid.

687
01:13:51,718 --> 01:13:58,141
And l am afraid to feel happiness.

688
01:13:58,308 --> 01:14:02,520
Afraid to hope for it again.

689
01:14:02,896 --> 01:14:06,899
l am afraid of God's judgment.

690
01:14:08,610 --> 01:14:13,573
[lN NORMAL VOlCE]
We serve a loving God, Thomas.

691
01:14:14,491 --> 01:14:18,035
We are in each other's arms.

692
01:14:18,787 --> 01:14:23,124
We are together,
and we are happy together.

693
01:14:23,292 --> 01:14:27,712
And is our love not proof of his?

694
01:14:29,047 --> 01:14:32,341
We must not fear, Thomas.

695
01:14:33,302 --> 01:14:36,345
We will survive this war.

696
01:14:37,097 --> 01:14:40,057
And we will have a child.

697
01:14:40,893 --> 01:14:43,478
So help us, God.

698
01:14:53,655 --> 01:14:55,239
[MARCHlNG BAND PLAYlNG
UPBEAT MUSlC]

699
01:15:05,584 --> 01:15:08,044
-Major Gilmore, stop that damn drumming!
-Quiet!

700
01:15:08,212 --> 01:15:11,422
-Stop that damn drumming!
-Quiet!

701
01:15:21,600 --> 01:15:23,142
This is a hell of a regiment.

702
01:15:24,686 --> 01:15:28,481
Men of the 20th Maine Regiment
of Volunteers. . .

703
01:15:28,690 --> 01:15:32,485
. ..this is your commanding officer,
Colonel Adelbert Ames.

704
01:15:32,653 --> 01:15:33,903
[CROWD CHEERlNG]

705
01:15:34,071 --> 01:15:35,738
Quiet! Quiet!

706
01:15:35,948 --> 01:15:39,367
You do not cheer an officer.

707
01:15:39,535 --> 01:15:40,826
You salute him.

708
01:15:41,620 --> 01:15:44,497
20th Maine, l commend you
for the enthusiasm...

709
01:15:44,665 --> 01:15:48,000
. ..that has made you volunteer
for service in Lincoln's Army.

710
01:15:48,835 --> 01:15:51,921
l can see that many of you
are strong and fit.

711
01:15:52,172 --> 01:15:55,633
We Maine men know that
life in the woods of Maine...

712
01:15:55,801 --> 01:15:58,636
. ..toughens the muscles
and stretches the sinews.

713
01:15:58,804 --> 01:16:02,223
l've no doubt many of you
have become good shots by hunting deer.

714
01:16:02,474 --> 01:16:07,311
But tough muscles and skillful shooting
are not enough to make a soldier.

715
01:16:07,479 --> 01:16:10,189
That requires discipline.

716
01:16:10,649 --> 01:16:14,694
Major Gilmore tells me you are in the habit
of holding discussions with your officers.

717
01:16:14,987 --> 01:16:17,446
That will cease from now.

718
01:16:17,656 --> 01:16:22,827
An officer's orders are to be obeyed
instantly and without question.

719
01:16:24,204 --> 01:16:27,748
This regiment must learn
to move as one man.

720
01:16:28,792 --> 01:16:31,711
Otherwise we will all be killed.

721
01:16:33,880 --> 01:16:36,299
-See if you can teach them to march.
-Yes, sir.

722
01:16:36,466 --> 01:16:38,217
Colonel Chamberlain.

723
01:16:39,803 --> 01:16:41,262
Come with me.

724
01:16:45,684 --> 01:16:49,395
When l say, "20th Maine, attention". . .

725
01:16:49,563 --> 01:16:51,856
. ..you bring your feet together.

726
01:16:52,024 --> 01:16:54,442
Governor Washburn
and Adjutant General Hodgson. . .

727
01:16:54,610 --> 01:16:56,986
. ..have sent me
an impressive report about you.

728
01:16:57,154 --> 01:17:00,156
They say you will master
any assignment you're given.

729
01:17:00,532 --> 01:17:03,034
l shall certainly try, sir.

730
01:17:04,703 --> 01:17:07,788
l, uh, understand you were in
the Battle of Bull Run.

731
01:17:07,956 --> 01:17:11,751
Wounded too. lt taught me the need
for discipline and proper procedure.

732
01:17:11,918 --> 01:17:14,003
Take the act of shooting, for example.

733
01:17:14,171 --> 01:17:17,882
When you're hunting in the Maine woods
there's no difficulty in loading a rifle.

734
01:17:18,050 --> 01:17:20,593
But in the panic of war,
men act foolishly.

735
01:17:20,761 --> 01:17:24,221
ln Bull Run l saw a soldier forget
to remove his ramrod from the barrel.

736
01:17:24,389 --> 01:17:27,350
When he fired,
out it flew with a dismal twang.

737
01:17:27,517 --> 01:17:31,312
He lost the means of firing again
and was killed soon after by a Rebel bullet.

738
01:17:45,952 --> 01:17:48,496
Sergeant Tom Chamberlain
reporting for duty, sir.

739
01:17:48,664 --> 01:17:50,748
Tom, what on earth--?
What are you doing?

740
01:17:50,916 --> 01:17:54,502
l signed up, Lawrence, l'm in this regiment.
l'm coming with you.

741
01:17:54,670 --> 01:17:57,421
Did Father approve?
How will he run the farm?

742
01:17:57,589 --> 01:18:00,383
Once he heard you were colonel,
he couldn't say no.

743
01:18:00,550 --> 01:18:03,386
Besides, you know him,
he'll be all right. They both will.

744
01:18:03,553 --> 01:18:05,763
l'm giving them one less thing to cuss at.

745
01:18:05,931 --> 01:18:10,393
Mama said so many prayers for the both
of us, we got nothing to worry about.

746
01:18:10,894 --> 01:18:14,647
Well, l guess l have one more responsibility.
l have to look after you.

747
01:18:15,273 --> 01:18:16,357
Me?

748
01:18:16,525 --> 01:18:19,485
Lawrence, Mama told me
to watch after you.

749
01:18:43,969 --> 01:18:48,931
Just remember, lads, even a tin cup
is a great weight after 20 mile.

750
01:18:49,099 --> 01:18:53,060
Your precarious pegs won't last
if you turn yourselves into pack mules.

751
01:18:53,228 --> 01:18:56,105
And only one leg to a pant, if you please.

752
01:18:56,356 --> 01:18:58,190
You'll soon be at the worn end of it...

753
01:18:58,358 --> 01:19:01,736
. ..where your formal attire will be
your shirt collar and boots.

754
01:19:02,320 --> 01:19:05,156
ln the U.S. Army we have
the School of the Soldier. . .

755
01:19:05,323 --> 01:19:08,075
. ..in which the soldier is trained
and by numbers drilled.

756
01:19:08,243 --> 01:19:10,703
Loading a musket
is done in nine movements. . .

757
01:19:10,871 --> 01:19:13,497
. ..performed over and over
until they become automatic. ..

758
01:19:13,665 --> 01:19:16,584
. ..or, as we call it, loading in nine times.

759
01:19:16,752 --> 01:19:18,461
Aah! l see. Sergeant Chamberlain.

760
01:19:18,628 --> 01:19:20,504
Loading in nine times. Demonstrate this.

761
01:19:20,839 --> 01:19:22,673
Assume the musket has just been fired.

762
01:19:22,841 --> 01:19:25,760
One, reach into cartridge box
and withdraw cartridge.

763
01:19:25,927 --> 01:19:28,888
Two, place cartridge between teeth.

764
01:19:29,055 --> 01:19:30,848
Three, tear paper open.

765
01:19:31,016 --> 01:19:34,685
Four, pour powder into barrel
and charge cartridge.

766
01:19:43,987 --> 01:19:47,865
Five, withdraw the ramrod.
Six, ram the ball home.

767
01:19:48,033 --> 01:19:49,867
Seven, return ramrod.

768
01:19:50,035 --> 01:19:52,369
Eight, half-cock the hammer...

769
01:19:52,537 --> 01:19:54,288
. ..remove old cap. ..

770
01:19:54,456 --> 01:19:57,041
. ..and put a new cap on the cone.

771
01:20:00,086 --> 01:20:02,254
Nine, shoulder arms.

772
01:20:02,923 --> 01:20:04,423
All right, you have the idea.

773
01:20:04,591 --> 01:20:08,677
But this must be done without thinking
and much, much faster.

774
01:20:08,845 --> 01:20:10,304
Here.

775
01:20:10,472 --> 01:20:13,015
One, two, three, four...

776
01:20:13,767 --> 01:20:15,434
. ..five...

777
01:20:16,728 --> 01:20:18,270


. ..six...

778
01:20:19,064 --> 01:20:20,898
. ..seven...

779
01:20:22,818 --> 01:20:24,360
. ..eight...

780
01:20:25,570 --> 01:20:26,987


. ..nine.

781
01:20:27,489 --> 01:20:29,782
Practice until you can do it
as fast as that.

782
01:20:29,950 --> 01:20:32,576
lt may save your lives. Colonel.

783
01:20:35,372 --> 01:20:38,791
Line of battle consists of two lines of men,
one behind the other. ..

784
01:20:38,959 --> 01:20:41,961
. ..so that while one line fires,
the other reloads.

785
01:20:42,128 --> 01:20:47,341
Behind them is a line of, uh, file closers.
Lieutenants and sergeants.

786
01:20:47,509 --> 01:20:50,094
But two lines make a regiment
unwieldy on the move...

787
01:20:50,262 --> 01:20:52,555
. ..so we need to switch to column of fours.

788
01:20:52,722 --> 01:20:56,267
We need to be able to change from
column of fours to line of battle. . .

789
01:20:56,434 --> 01:20:58,102
. ..and back again quickly.

790
01:20:58,270 --> 01:21:01,564
lt is not difficult to move from line of battle
into column of fours.

791
01:21:01,731 --> 01:21:05,025
lt is harder to move from
column of fours into line of battle...

792
01:21:05,193 --> 01:21:09,071
...and if we're called to make that move,
it will be when we're under fire.

793
01:21:09,239 --> 01:21:13,701
You understand how important it is that
these moves are learned so thoroughly...

794
01:21:13,869 --> 01:21:17,079
...that the men can perform them
in their sleep.

795
01:21:26,631 --> 01:21:28,966
Company. . .

796
01:21:29,634 --> 01:21:31,552
. ..halt!

797
01:21:32,554 --> 01:21:35,890
Company, front!

798
01:21:39,853 --> 01:21:42,313
Order arms!

799
01:21:52,282 --> 01:21:54,825
Well done, colonel. That's a beginning.

800
01:21:54,993 --> 01:21:58,287
But that move must be practiced
and practiced and practiced.

801
01:21:58,496 --> 01:22:00,372
Another month and we'll be ready.

802
01:22:00,540 --> 01:22:03,500
But we leave for Washington tomorrow.

803
01:22:08,840 --> 01:22:11,550
Shoulder arms!

804
01:22:13,803 --> 01:22:17,890
Company, forward march!

805
01:22:18,058 --> 01:22:19,183
[SOLDlER PLAYlNG DRUM]

806
01:22:32,197 --> 01:22:36,867
Gentlemen, it's only September.
Too soon for winter camp.

807
01:22:37,035 --> 01:22:39,370
We have the momentum.

808
01:22:39,746 --> 01:22:42,539
l propose we advance our army
north into Maryland...

809
01:22:42,707 --> 01:22:45,960
. ..because there the farms are plentiful
and nearly untouched.

810
01:22:46,211 --> 01:22:49,964
And with a fall harvest,
we could feed our troops very well indeed.

811
01:22:50,131 --> 01:22:52,549
And there is one other consideration.

812
01:22:52,717 --> 01:22:55,636
Maryland is being held in the Union
by force.

813
01:22:55,804 --> 01:22:59,890
Our arrival may be viewed as a liberation.

814
01:23:00,058 --> 01:23:02,851
We might receive some hospitality.

815
01:23:03,019 --> 01:23:06,981
Might even receive a number of volunteers
for service in the Army.

816
01:23:07,148 --> 01:23:11,151
General, might this not be considered
an invasion?

817
01:23:11,319 --> 01:23:13,988
l don't believe so, general. No, sir.

818
01:23:14,155 --> 01:23:16,073
With the Federal invasion of Virginia. . .

819
01:23:16,241 --> 01:23:18,909
. ..the Confederacy proved
who's the aggressor here.

820
01:23:19,077 --> 01:23:20,911
We did not bring this war...

821
01:23:21,079 --> 01:23:24,331
. ..and we fight now only to free the South
of Federal occupation.

822
01:23:26,209 --> 01:23:28,002
As l've said many times. . .

823
01:23:28,169 --> 01:23:32,464
. ..if Washington will end their side
of the fighting and recall their armies...

824
01:23:32,632 --> 01:23:34,425
. ..this war will be over.

825
01:23:35,051 --> 01:23:37,094
But in the meantime...

826
01:23:37,762 --> 01:23:40,514
. ..we must show the enemy
that they cannot win.

827
01:23:40,682 --> 01:23:42,558
Cannot win.

828
01:23:42,726 --> 01:23:46,812
Now, by moving into Maryland, we'd be
in a position to push into Pennsylvania.

829
01:23:46,980 --> 01:23:51,734
And so far, gentlemen,
the bloody fields are Southern fields.

830
01:23:52,360 --> 01:23:54,611
lf we threaten the Northern cities...

831
01:23:54,779 --> 01:23:58,115
. ..if we threaten to bring the blood
into the North. . .

832
01:23:59,826 --> 01:24:02,161
. ..there'll be pressure on Lincoln
to end this war.

833
01:24:02,328 --> 01:24:03,704
Amen.

834
01:24:04,998 --> 01:24:09,043
Our presence, just the threat,
could be sufficient.

835
01:24:09,210 --> 01:24:10,377
LONGSTREET:
General Lee...

836
01:24:10,879 --> 01:24:15,674
. ..we'd be cutting ourselves off from
our base of supplies, communications.

837
01:24:15,842 --> 01:24:17,676
We'd be vulnerable from the rear, sir.

838
01:24:17,844 --> 01:24:21,138
General Longstreet, you marched
into Mexico with General Scott?

839
01:24:21,765 --> 01:24:22,848
Yes, sir.

840
01:24:23,016 --> 01:24:26,727
LEE: Did not General Scott cut himself off
from his supplies and communication?

841
01:24:27,312 --> 01:24:31,440
And by so doing,
did he not bring a rapid end to that war?

842
01:24:31,941 --> 01:24:34,693
And did he not accomplish all of that
in a foreign land?

843
01:24:35,695 --> 01:24:37,988
Well, this is not a foreign land.

844
01:24:38,156 --> 01:24:42,034
The citizens will see we're not coming
to vandalize as the Yankees did to us.

845
01:24:42,202 --> 01:24:44,161
We've come to end the war quickly. . .

846
01:24:44,329 --> 01:24:47,081
. ..and without any need
to conquer or subdue anyone.

847
01:24:49,834 --> 01:24:52,377
We proved our superiority
on the battlefield.

848
01:24:52,545 --> 01:24:55,798
That superiority may be
all we need, gentlemen.

849
01:24:55,965 --> 01:24:58,092
All we need.

850
01:24:58,259 --> 01:25:00,636
-General Lee?
-Yes.

851
01:25:00,804 --> 01:25:03,806
Pleased to hear we're finally
taking the war to the enemy.

852
01:25:03,973 --> 01:25:06,683
Let them feel the scourge
of this war that they began.

853
01:25:06,851 --> 01:25:08,435
Yes, sir.

854
01:25:08,812 --> 01:25:12,106
SOLDlERS [SlNGlNG]:
His torch is at thy temple door

855
01:25:12,524 --> 01:25:16,318
Maryland, my Maryland

856
01:25:16,486 --> 01:25:20,614
Avenge the patriotic gore

857
01:25:20,782 --> 01:25:24,493
That flecked the streets of Baltimore

858
01:25:24,661 --> 01:25:29,039
And be the battle queen of yore

859
01:25:29,207 --> 01:25:33,252
Maryland, my Maryland

860
01:25:45,265 --> 01:25:48,433
Morning to you, sir.
Colonel Ames sent me to get you.

861
01:25:48,601 --> 01:25:52,771
-Said you might be needing a drop of this.
-Ah. Thank you. ...

862
01:25:52,981 --> 01:25:58,152
Kilrain, sir. Sergeant Kilrain.
Glad to be of service.

863
01:25:59,154 --> 01:26:01,280
You know, colonel, uh...

864
01:26:01,447 --> 01:26:03,740
. ..the boys. . . .

865
01:26:03,908 --> 01:26:06,285
We've been watching you, sir,
that we have.

866
01:26:06,786 --> 01:26:10,539
You've learned fast.
Becoming a pleasure to serve under you.

867
01:26:10,707 --> 01:26:12,457
Yes, well, ahem....

868
01:26:12,625 --> 01:26:14,877
Are you a, uh, veteran, sergeant?

869
01:26:15,044 --> 01:26:17,796
Aye, sir. l suppose you could say that.

870
01:26:17,964 --> 01:26:20,465
Did me duty in the regular Army
for a while.

871
01:26:20,758 --> 01:26:25,470
Did the great long walk with General Scott,
down south of the Rio Grande.

872
01:26:25,972 --> 01:26:30,642
Uh, some men you fought with are on
the other side. Almost all of their generals.

873
01:26:30,935 --> 01:26:34,313
Oh, it gets worse than generals, colonel.

874
01:26:34,480 --> 01:26:39,776
Some of the lads that l left lreland with
are on the other side as well. lmagine that.

875
01:26:39,944 --> 01:26:42,321
We left together to escape a tyranny...

876
01:26:42,864 --> 01:26:46,825
. ..and end up shooting at one another
in the land of the free.

877
01:26:50,121 --> 01:26:53,290
l, too, have friends
on the other side, sergeant.

878
01:26:54,667 --> 01:26:56,001
And enemies.

879
01:26:57,003 --> 01:26:58,670
Yes, sir.

880
01:26:58,838 --> 01:27:02,466
No shortage of enemies, that's for sure.

881
01:27:10,308 --> 01:27:11,934
We're ordered to remain in place.

882
01:27:12,101 --> 01:27:14,394
The army is spreading out
a couple miles up.

883
01:27:14,562 --> 01:27:16,897
The enemy is dug in
behind a small creek.

884
01:27:17,065 --> 01:27:19,900
Antietam Creek,
just this side of Sharpsburg.

885
01:27:20,068 --> 01:27:22,319
We may be put into the battle
at any time.

886
01:27:22,487 --> 01:27:26,073
For now, get the men to step it up,
finish breakfast and wait for orders.

887
01:27:26,241 --> 01:27:28,325
-Got that?
-Certainly, colonel.

888
01:27:30,870 --> 01:27:32,162
[GUNFlRE NEARBY]

889
01:27:33,498 --> 01:27:36,833
Whose guns are those?
Has the attack begun?

890
01:27:37,543 --> 01:27:41,713
Likely it's the first feeling-out,
probing, testing of strength.

891
01:27:42,382 --> 01:27:44,675
lt's a game to the artillery boys. . .

892
01:27:44,842 --> 01:27:47,844
. ..letting you know they can hit you
when the time comes.

893
01:27:50,265 --> 01:27:53,308
Lawrence. Lawrence, lookie here.

894
01:27:53,559 --> 01:27:55,477
This is what we've been eating
every day.

895
01:27:56,354 --> 01:27:59,106
But you know what?
l've gained some weight.

896
01:27:59,274 --> 01:28:01,942
Hard to believe a man could
gain some weight on a diet of worms.

897
01:28:02,110 --> 01:28:03,235
[CHUCKLES]

898
01:28:04,445 --> 01:28:07,322
Well, best eat up, sergeant.
We're moving out.

899
01:28:38,146 --> 01:28:39,771
Good morning, sir.

900
01:28:39,939 --> 01:28:42,899
The Yankees are coming thick and fast
in the woods before us.

901
01:28:43,693 --> 01:28:45,110
We're making it hot for them.

902
01:28:45,695 --> 01:28:48,071
We must hold this ridge. We must.

903
01:28:48,239 --> 01:28:49,573
So pour it to them, Reverend.

904
01:28:50,450 --> 01:28:51,616
Sir.

905
01:28:54,037 --> 01:28:56,538
ROB:
Sir, it's me, Rob.

906
01:28:56,831 --> 01:28:58,832
My dear son. How are you, boy?

907
01:28:59,000 --> 01:29:00,250
l'm well, sir.

908
01:29:00,418 --> 01:29:04,004
l congratulate you for being
in the fight and unhurt.

909
01:29:04,172 --> 01:29:06,214
May God keep you so.

910
01:29:06,549 --> 01:29:10,052
And remember, son, we must do
all we can to drive these people back.

911
01:29:10,219 --> 01:29:12,888
Yes, sir. We'll do our best, sir.

912
01:29:13,222 --> 01:29:14,306
SOLDlER:
Fire!

913
01:29:37,288 --> 01:29:38,622
[SOLDlERS SCREAMlNG]

914
01:29:53,596 --> 01:29:57,265
Mr. Pendleton, ride to General Hood,
ask him can he maintain his position?

915
01:29:57,433 --> 01:30:00,143
Yes, sir, can he maintain his position?

916
01:30:00,311 --> 01:30:02,729
Hyah, hyah!

917
01:30:09,654 --> 01:30:10,821
Fire!

918
01:30:15,576 --> 01:30:16,827
Reload!

919
01:30:18,413 --> 01:30:19,538
Fire!

920
01:30:21,666 --> 01:30:23,667
lt's good to be sergeant, isn't it?

921
01:30:23,835 --> 01:30:26,545
To shoot a sergeant,
you have to fire through two men.

922
01:30:26,712 --> 01:30:30,966
A sergeant never fires his weapon
until the men in front of him are killed. . .

923
01:30:31,134 --> 01:30:34,052
. ..and then only unless
you want to show off.

924
01:30:41,102 --> 01:30:44,104
Move the men into this field
and wait for further orders.

925
01:30:44,272 --> 01:30:45,730
We're part of the reserve.

926
01:30:47,066 --> 01:30:50,193
-Battalion, forward!
-Forward!

927
01:30:50,361 --> 01:30:51,570
[SOLDlER PLAYlNG BUGLE]

928
01:30:53,739 --> 01:30:55,198
March!

929
01:31:08,421 --> 01:31:09,588
[BOTH SHOUTlNG]

930
01:31:17,180 --> 01:31:18,722
Compliments from General Jackson.

931
01:31:18,890 --> 01:31:21,057
He wants to know,
can you maintain position?

932
01:31:21,225 --> 01:31:24,394
Tell General Jackson
unless l get reinforcements. . .

933
01:31:24,562 --> 01:31:26,062
. .. l must be forced back.

934
01:31:26,230 --> 01:31:28,482
But l'm going on while l can.

935
01:31:28,816 --> 01:31:31,067
Yes, sir. Reinforcements. Yes, sir.

936
01:31:32,445 --> 01:31:33,904
[SOLDlERS SHOUTlNG AND GRUNTlNG]

937
01:31:39,076 --> 01:31:40,452
-Load!
-Load!

938
01:31:42,538 --> 01:31:44,164
Take aim!

939
01:31:44,624 --> 01:31:45,749
Fire!

940
01:31:48,836 --> 01:31:50,378
Forward, men, forward!

941
01:31:50,546 --> 01:31:51,671
Fire!

942
01:31:52,673 --> 01:31:54,007
[SOLDlERS SCREAMlNG]

943
01:32:16,113 --> 01:32:18,907
-General McClellan, sir.
-General Hancock.

944
01:32:19,075 --> 01:32:21,743
Had you heard that General Richardson
had been wounded?

945
01:32:21,911 --> 01:32:23,119
l heard he'd been wounded.

946
01:32:23,412 --> 01:32:26,790
l'm sorry to tell you it is serious
and you will assume his command.

947
01:32:26,958 --> 01:32:29,626
Yes, sir. Of course, sir.

948
01:32:29,794 --> 01:32:31,545
l'm honored to accept the command.

949
01:32:31,963 --> 01:32:33,713
l'm sure you will perform this duty. ..

950
01:32:33,881 --> 01:32:36,424
. ..with the skill and courage
you have shown already.

951
01:32:36,801 --> 01:32:41,721
We are on the move now, and we will drive
the Rebels into the river before the sun sets.

952
01:32:41,889 --> 01:32:44,724
Hold this position against
any assault by the enemy.

953
01:32:57,113 --> 01:32:58,405
Reply from General Hood:

954
01:32:58,573 --> 01:33:01,908
"Tell Jackson unless l get reinforcements,
l must be forced back."

955
01:33:02,076 --> 01:33:04,327
-But he will go on while he can.
-Good, good.

956
01:33:04,495 --> 01:33:06,371
General McLaws, advance your--

957
01:33:17,300 --> 01:33:19,009
Captain Morrison.

958
01:33:19,176 --> 01:33:21,803
l think it advisable
you keep your distance from me.

959
01:33:21,971 --> 01:33:26,349
lt would not do for Anna to lose both
a husband and a brother on the same day.

960
01:33:37,945 --> 01:33:41,197
Battalion, halt!

961
01:33:44,702 --> 01:33:47,120
The battle may be moving our way.
Keep them ready.

962
01:33:47,288 --> 01:33:48,371
Yes, sir.

963
01:34:10,853 --> 01:34:13,980
Courtesy of a lady admirer in Sharpsburg.

964
01:34:26,035 --> 01:34:28,787
Think we can hold out
against another attack?

965
01:34:28,954 --> 01:34:31,164
l think they have done their worst.

966
01:34:31,999 --> 01:34:34,793
l think there's little danger
of our line being broken.

967
01:34:54,438 --> 01:34:56,648
We won't be needed today, colonel.

968
01:35:01,529 --> 01:35:06,741
The 5th Corps was not
needed today, gentlemen.

969
01:35:09,870 --> 01:35:14,040
Not according to the judgment
of our commanding general.

970
01:35:15,042 --> 01:35:17,794
The battle has been extremely costly.

971
01:35:18,212 --> 01:35:22,549
The enemy has been checked,
at great loss to both sides.

972
01:35:24,051 --> 01:35:28,012
From what we can observe so far,
we've gained little.

973
01:35:29,473 --> 01:35:31,850
lt's possible the fight
will resume tomorrow.

974
01:35:46,866 --> 01:35:50,493
He that created us
gave us such strong argument. . .

975
01:35:50,661 --> 01:35:55,665
. ..starting before and after,
gave us not capabilities...

976
01:35:55,833 --> 01:36:00,503
. ..and divine reason
to fust inside of us unused.

977
01:36:01,672 --> 01:36:06,301
Now, whether it be bestial oblivion,
or some craven scruple. . .

978
01:36:06,469 --> 01:36:08,678
. ..of thinking too precisely
on the event. ..

979
01:36:08,846 --> 01:36:11,848
. ..a thought which, quartered,
hath but one part one wisdom...

980
01:36:12,016 --> 01:36:14,434
. ..and ever three parts coward...

981
01:36:15,269 --> 01:36:20,607
. .. l do not know why yet l live to say
"This thing's to do"...

982
01:36:20,775 --> 01:36:27,030
. ..sith l have cause and will and strength
and means to do it.

983
01:36:27,198 --> 01:36:29,657
Examples gross as earth exhort me:

984
01:36:29,825 --> 01:36:34,287
Witness this army
of such mass and charge...

985
01:36:34,455 --> 01:36:37,791
...led by a delicate and tender prince...

986
01:36:38,167 --> 01:36:42,045
...whose spirit
with divine ambition puffed...

987
01:36:42,213 --> 01:36:46,049
...makes mouths at the invisible event...

988
01:36:46,217 --> 01:36:49,052
...exposing what is mortal and unsure...

989
01:36:49,220 --> 01:36:56,017
...to all that death and danger dare,
even for an egg-shell.

990
01:36:56,894 --> 01:36:59,729
Rightly to be great
is not to stir without great argument...

991
01:36:59,897 --> 01:37:04,192
...but greatly to find quarrel in a straw
when honor's at the stake.

992
01:37:04,360 --> 01:37:06,861
How stand l then...

993
01:37:07,780 --> 01:37:10,281
...that have a father killed...

994
01:37:10,866 --> 01:37:12,951
...a mother stained...

995
01:37:13,118 --> 01:37:15,537
...excitements of my reason
and my blood...

996
01:37:15,704 --> 01:37:18,456
...and let all sleep?

997
01:37:18,624 --> 01:37:21,584
While, to my shame, l see...

998
01:37:21,752 --> 01:37:26,172
. ..the imminent death of 20,000 men.. .

999
01:37:27,049 --> 01:37:29,634
. ..that, for a fantasy or trick of fame...

1000
01:37:29,802 --> 01:37:34,556
. ..go to their graves like beds,
fight for a plot. . .

1001
01:37:35,724 --> 01:37:38,017
. ..whereon the numbers
cannot try the cause...

1002
01:37:40,271 --> 01:37:44,524
. ..which is not tomb enough or continent
to hide the slain?

1003
01:37:45,067 --> 01:37:50,280
O, from this time forth...

1004
01:37:51,907 --> 01:37:54,701
. ..my thoughts be bloody. . .

1005
01:37:55,202 --> 01:37:58,121
. ..or be nothing worth.

1006
01:38:06,422 --> 01:38:08,506
He's mad. Did you see this?

1007
01:38:08,674 --> 01:38:11,301
lt's nothing less than a call
for a slave uprising.

1008
01:38:11,468 --> 01:38:15,471
Darling, l hardly ever get to see you.

1009
01:38:15,639 --> 01:38:18,141
Can't we put away the paper
this one evening?

1010
01:38:18,309 --> 01:38:20,977
lt'll put you in the foulest mood.
lt always does.

1011
01:38:21,145 --> 01:38:23,396
Well, here. Read it for yourself.

1012
01:38:23,564 --> 01:38:27,066
Lincoln plans a general emancipation
on New Year's Day. . .

1013
01:38:27,985 --> 01:38:30,528
. ..for all slaves
from states still in rebellion.

1014
01:38:30,696 --> 01:38:36,117
Yet another page from the Constitution
torn to shreds.

1015
01:38:36,619 --> 01:38:39,537
But this is harmless, John.

1016
01:38:39,705 --> 01:38:41,789
See, it says right here:

1017
01:38:41,957 --> 01:38:46,044
"An emancipation of all slaves
from the states still in rebellion."

1018
01:38:46,211 --> 01:38:47,420
But can't you see?

1019
01:38:47,671 --> 01:38:52,467
Those are the very states where the
president has no authority and no power.

1020
01:38:54,094 --> 01:38:57,096
Why, yes. You're quite right.

1021
01:38:57,473 --> 01:38:59,849
l hadn't considered it in that light.

1022
01:39:00,434 --> 01:39:06,147
Now, can we fold up the paper
into a nice little square. . .

1023
01:39:06,357 --> 01:39:09,567
. ..so that l can cut it up
into a hundred little pieces. . .

1024
01:39:09,735 --> 01:39:11,527
. ..and throw it into the street?

1025
01:39:11,695 --> 01:39:12,904
[CHUCKLES]

1026
01:39:13,238 --> 01:39:14,656
Hmm.

1027
01:39:15,574 --> 01:39:19,577
Boyo, another round, if you please.

1028
01:39:21,538 --> 01:39:22,747
[BAND PLAYlNG SOMBER MUSlC]

1029
01:39:38,931 --> 01:39:43,393
Now, it says here in Blackmantle's
Art of Punning...

1030
01:39:43,560 --> 01:39:48,564
. ..that "punning is an art of harmonious
jingling upon words...

1031
01:39:48,732 --> 01:39:52,485
. ..which, passing in at the ears
and falling upon the diaphragm...

1032
01:39:52,653 --> 01:39:56,447
. ..excites a titillary motion
in those parts. . .

1033
01:39:56,615 --> 01:39:57,907
[BOTH LAUGHlNG]

1034
01:39:58,075 --> 01:40:02,578
. ..and this, being conveyed by the
animal spirits into the muscles of the face.. .

1035
01:40:02,746 --> 01:40:05,081
. ..raises the cockles of the heart."

1036
01:40:07,251 --> 01:40:09,752
All right, then. ls everyone ready?

1037
01:40:09,920 --> 01:40:12,255
-Sure, why not?
-Yes, sir.

1038
01:40:12,423 --> 01:40:14,590
Counties of England.

1039
01:40:14,758 --> 01:40:18,219
Who has the most dogs?

1040
01:40:22,725 --> 01:40:24,267
Bark-shire.

1041
01:40:24,435 --> 01:40:27,061
-Ha, ha.
-Well done.

1042
01:40:27,771 --> 01:40:30,356
And from where did
the first hermaphrodites come from?

1043
01:40:32,026 --> 01:40:34,736
Oh. Um, Middlesex.

1044
01:40:35,863 --> 01:40:39,157
Yeah. And from whence
the first circus tumblers came?

1045
01:40:40,951 --> 01:40:42,952
Circus tumblers?

1046
01:40:45,456 --> 01:40:50,835
Somerset.

1047
01:40:51,003 --> 01:40:52,837
-Oh, Lord.
-Somerset.

1048
01:40:54,006 --> 01:40:56,466
Well, l can see you've all learned
rule number six:

1049
01:40:56,633 --> 01:40:59,719
Never speak well of another punster
and never laugh at his puns.

1050
01:41:00,137 --> 01:41:01,387
[LAUGH lNG]

1051
01:41:01,805 --> 01:41:02,889
Somerset.

1052
01:41:05,809 --> 01:41:07,894
The Rebel sharpshooters
was in the house.

1053
01:41:08,062 --> 01:41:10,980
That's what made them Yankees
shell it so.

1054
01:41:11,482 --> 01:41:14,150
-Where was this?
-Outside Winchester.

1055
01:41:14,318 --> 01:41:18,863
Them Yankees been through that town
more times than there is flies on a mule.

1056
01:41:19,073 --> 01:41:20,490
Mm.

1057
01:41:20,824 --> 01:41:22,200
Where's your master now?

1058
01:41:23,827 --> 01:41:25,661
l ain't got no master no more.

1059
01:41:25,829 --> 01:41:27,580
Now he my boss.

1060
01:41:28,165 --> 01:41:31,501
See, l was sold at auction
over in Fredericksburg once...

1061
01:41:31,668 --> 01:41:34,879
. ..and he bought me for $1 200.

1062
01:41:35,589 --> 01:41:39,008
Then the war come,
that didn't set right with him...

1063
01:41:39,176 --> 01:41:41,052
. ..so he gave me my freedom papers.

1064
01:41:42,179 --> 01:41:44,514
Now he pays me wages.

1065
01:41:44,932 --> 01:41:47,725
-No, sir.
-Thirty dollars a month.

1066
01:41:48,227 --> 01:41:49,268
What he pay you for?

1067
01:41:50,104 --> 01:41:52,939
l can do anything l turn my hands to.

1068
01:41:53,232 --> 01:41:55,691
Then them Yankees come
and burned down his house...

1069
01:41:55,859 --> 01:41:59,028
. ..and the next thing you know,
the man who's paying me wages. ..

1070
01:41:59,196 --> 01:42:03,407
. ..is in the Confederate Army.
And so am l.

1071
01:42:04,368 --> 01:42:05,743
[BOTH LAUGHlNG]

1072
01:42:07,454 --> 01:42:10,373
-Man, that's good!
-Let's do this thing right here.

1073
01:42:10,791 --> 01:42:13,501
Hey, come on. Check it.

1074
01:42:24,346 --> 01:42:26,139
No, no, no. Gentlemen.

1075
01:42:26,682 --> 01:42:28,307
Stay where you are.

1076
01:42:28,976 --> 01:42:30,685
Greetings.

1077
01:42:31,728 --> 01:42:33,271
General.

1078
01:42:33,689 --> 01:42:36,232
[SPEAKlNG lN FORElGN LANGUAGE]

1079
01:42:37,317 --> 01:42:39,902
How is our fine Prussian officer
this evening?

1080
01:42:40,070 --> 01:42:43,281
l would've thought General Stuart
would've had you at least. . .

1081
01:42:43,448 --> 01:42:45,366
. ..20 miles behind enemy lines...

1082
01:42:45,534 --> 01:42:48,411
. ..creating havoc and bewilderment
in Washington.

1083
01:42:48,912 --> 01:42:50,246
[LAUGH lNG]

1084
01:42:50,664 --> 01:42:53,791
l would certainly prefer such a mission.

1085
01:42:54,418 --> 01:42:56,169
But tonight. . .

1086
01:42:57,045 --> 01:43:01,549
. ..tonight, general,
l come bringing you a present.

1087
01:43:02,426 --> 01:43:04,260
General Jackson.. .

1088
01:43:04,428 --> 01:43:08,055
. .. l am greatly pleased to bring
this present from General Stuart.

1089
01:43:09,099 --> 01:43:15,188
The general has gone to great lengths
to secure for you this.

1090
01:43:16,940 --> 01:43:19,775
Would you like for me
to open that for you, sir?

1091
01:43:21,111 --> 01:43:22,612
Thank you.

1092
01:43:33,624 --> 01:43:34,957
General.

1093
01:43:36,460 --> 01:43:38,961
This is some fine material. Look here.

1094
01:43:40,297 --> 01:43:42,131
That's gold braid.

1095
01:43:47,804 --> 01:43:51,849
You may tell General Stuart
that l deeply appreciate this gift.

1096
01:43:52,017 --> 01:43:54,268
Please assure the general...

1097
01:43:54,436 --> 01:43:57,021
. .. l will treat it with the utmost of care.. .

1098
01:43:57,648 --> 01:44:00,107
. ..and see that no harm comes to it.

1099
01:44:06,156 --> 01:44:09,617
Mr. Pendleton, will you kindly
place that uniform in my tent.

1100
01:44:09,952 --> 01:44:12,954
-And keep it neatly folded.
-Sir.

1101
01:44:13,121 --> 01:44:15,164
No, general, no.

1102
01:44:16,208 --> 01:44:18,167
You do not understand.

1103
01:44:18,710 --> 01:44:22,296
General Stuart was most insistent.

1104
01:44:23,632 --> 01:44:27,301
He says now that you are
a leutnant general...

1105
01:44:28,136 --> 01:44:30,930
. ..corps commander,
you deserve a new uniform.

1106
01:44:31,223 --> 01:44:34,016
He was most insistent you try it on.

1107
01:44:34,559 --> 01:44:38,187
He will certainly ask, "How was the fit?"

1108
01:44:40,023 --> 01:44:42,441
Please, general.

1109
01:44:43,485 --> 01:44:44,735
Try it on.

1110
01:45:13,890 --> 01:45:15,141
[CHUCKLES]

1111
01:45:15,392 --> 01:45:19,562
General, that's some mighty fine coat.
Ha, ha.

1112
01:45:19,730 --> 01:45:21,022
[ALL CHUCKLlNG]

1113
01:45:28,780 --> 01:45:30,239
[SOLDlERS SHOUTlNG]

1114
01:46:04,191 --> 01:46:07,568
That is the sweetest music l ever heard.

1115
01:46:27,631 --> 01:46:29,715
Ah, gentlemen.

1116
01:46:30,300 --> 01:46:31,884
Excuse us, General Burnside...

1117
01:46:32,052 --> 01:46:35,054
. ..General Hancock has information
you may find useful.

1118
01:46:35,222 --> 01:46:38,974
Yes, General Hancock, a pleasure.
Sumner, come.

1119
01:46:39,142 --> 01:46:40,559
We have visitors.

1120
01:46:40,727 --> 01:46:45,022
Sir, General Hancock reports the river
can be forded the short way upstream.

1121
01:46:45,190 --> 01:46:50,736
There'll be no difficulty crossing. With
your permission, we can move right away.

1122
01:46:50,904 --> 01:46:54,198
General Hancock, l appreciate your efforts
at reconnaissance...

1123
01:46:54,366 --> 01:46:57,993
. ..but this possibility has been
considered and rejected.

1124
01:46:58,161 --> 01:47:00,037
The pontoons will be here any time.

1125
01:47:00,205 --> 01:47:03,749
We'll cross with not only the men
but also the wagons and supplies.

1126
01:47:03,917 --> 01:47:07,753
lt would be foolhardy to send the men
without the wagons, the big guns--

1127
01:47:07,921 --> 01:47:10,339
Excuse me, am l correct
in my observation...

1128
01:47:10,507 --> 01:47:13,759
. ..that there's little force opposing us
across the river?

1129
01:47:13,927 --> 01:47:15,594
Yes, you're absolutely correct.

1130
01:47:15,762 --> 01:47:18,347
For once we seem to have caught
Lee by surprise.

1131
01:47:18,515 --> 01:47:23,686
Then, sir, if l may suggest,
isn't it possible Lee is moving this way?

1132
01:47:24,354 --> 01:47:28,816
Certainly he's aware of our intentions.
lf we could occupy the town with infantry...

1133
01:47:28,984 --> 01:47:32,528
. ..it would make our job much easier
when the bridges do arrive.

1134
01:47:32,696 --> 01:47:36,365
Yes, but that's risky. Those men
could be cut off. ln this weather?

1135
01:47:36,533 --> 01:47:40,202
lt snows one day, melts the next.
The river could rise unexpectedly.

1136
01:47:40,370 --> 01:47:45,166
lt will be best, l assure you, if we wait
until the entire Army can cross together.

1137
01:47:45,333 --> 01:47:48,210
General Burnside, if we don't cross
the river soon...

1138
01:47:48,378 --> 01:47:51,213
. ..General Lee will make every effort
to stop us.

1139
01:47:51,798 --> 01:47:54,550
He will not let us move
toward Richmond unopposed.

1140
01:47:54,718 --> 01:47:56,886
Where are General Jackson's forces now?

1141
01:47:57,053 --> 01:47:59,638
Shouldn't we attempt to occupy
Fredericksburg. . .

1142
01:47:59,806 --> 01:48:04,310
. ..and possibly the Heights beyond now,
while we have it for the taking?

1143
01:48:04,478 --> 01:48:10,024
Please allow me, sir, to at least send
General Hancock's division across the river.

1144
01:48:10,192 --> 01:48:13,235
Surely they can carry
enough supplies with them...

1145
01:48:13,403 --> 01:48:18,657
. ..and the artillery from this side can protect
them against any advance by Lee.

1146
01:48:20,494 --> 01:48:26,916
Gentlemen, we will cross this river
when the bridges arrive and not before.

1147
01:48:27,083 --> 01:48:30,711
l do not have the luxury of deviating
from the larger plan.

1148
01:48:30,879 --> 01:48:34,089
The president approved my strategy,
and l shall stick to it.

1149
01:48:34,257 --> 01:48:40,012
Once this Army is across the river,
we will advance on Richmond in force.

1150
01:48:41,515 --> 01:48:43,599
We must not allow him. ..

1151
01:48:43,767 --> 01:48:48,354
. ..the luxury of attacking us as divided and
separated units as he's done in the past.

1152
01:48:48,522 --> 01:48:51,941
And l will not make the same mistake
as my predecessors.

1153
01:48:52,108 --> 01:48:55,027
So no, General Hancock.

1154
01:48:55,195 --> 01:48:58,572
You will stay on this side
until the pontoons are in place. . .

1155
01:48:58,740 --> 01:49:02,368
. ..and the entire Army crosses together.

1156
01:49:02,536 --> 01:49:06,747
An irresistible, impregnable force.

1157
01:49:13,547 --> 01:49:17,800
TAYLOR: Did you know George Washington
spent his boyhood not far from here?

1158
01:49:18,385 --> 01:49:22,388
And across that river, he's supposed
to have thrown that silver dollar...

1159
01:49:22,556 --> 01:49:25,474
. ..and cut down that cherry tree.

1160
01:49:25,892 --> 01:49:30,813
That may be so, Mr. Taylor, but it has
an even greater significance for me.

1161
01:49:31,064 --> 01:49:33,399
lt's where l met my wife.

1162
01:49:33,567 --> 01:49:37,361
That's something these Yankees
do not understand, will never understand.

1163
01:49:37,988 --> 01:49:41,323
You see these rivers and valleys
and streams...

1164
01:49:41,491 --> 01:49:44,159
. ..and fields, even towns?

1165
01:49:44,327 --> 01:49:48,998
They're just markings on a map to those
people in the war office in Washington.

1166
01:49:49,165 --> 01:49:54,503
But to us, my goodness,
they're birthplaces and burial grounds.

1167
01:49:54,671 --> 01:49:57,590
They're battlefields
where our ancestors fought...

1168
01:49:57,757 --> 01:50:01,302
. ..places where you and l learned
to walk, to talk and to pray.

1169
01:50:01,511 --> 01:50:07,182
Places where we made friendships
and, oh, yes, fell in love.

1170
01:50:08,435 --> 01:50:13,522
And they're the incarnation
of all our memories, Mr. Taylor. . .

1171
01:50:15,066 --> 01:50:17,610
. ..and all that we are.

1172
01:50:18,445 --> 01:50:20,946
All that we are.

1173
01:50:53,563 --> 01:50:57,566
-What place is this?
-Chancellor's Crossing.

1174
01:50:57,734 --> 01:51:01,153
We're another two hours or so
from Fredericksburg.

1175
01:51:01,821 --> 01:51:04,323
We'll rest here for a short time.

1176
01:51:04,491 --> 01:51:07,910
Yes, sir. l'll see what
the good folks can provide.

1177
01:51:16,753 --> 01:51:20,506
The general be fixing to eat
something warm?

1178
01:51:20,674 --> 01:51:22,424
No, no, Jim.

1179
01:51:22,592 --> 01:51:25,844
We gotta ride on straight
through to General Lee.

1180
01:51:26,012 --> 01:51:29,014
Don't want to get all warmed up
just to feel the cold all over again.

1181
01:51:29,182 --> 01:51:30,432
[CHUCKLES]

1182
01:51:31,601 --> 01:51:34,019
You never seem to mind the cold much.

1183
01:51:34,187 --> 01:51:38,691
Oh. l minds it. l just don't shows it.

1184
01:51:40,276 --> 01:51:43,779
Now, Little Sorrel,
l know this corn look poorly...

1185
01:51:43,947 --> 01:51:47,616
. ..but it sure beats no corn at all.

1186
01:51:55,041 --> 01:51:58,210
You heard from your family lately?

1187
01:51:59,045 --> 01:52:02,381
Ain't heared much for some time.

1188
01:52:02,549 --> 01:52:07,136
Yankee mail used to move
quicker than Secesh mail.

1189
01:52:10,640 --> 01:52:16,729
Lord, from where you sit
you can see the great distance...

1190
01:52:16,896 --> 01:52:20,315
. ..that separates our Southern men
from their wives and children.

1191
01:52:20,984 --> 01:52:24,570
We pray that you watch over our families.

1192
01:52:25,989 --> 01:52:29,241
Lord, l ask you to watch over
Jim Lewis' family...

1193
01:52:29,409 --> 01:52:33,328
. ..over his friends, his loved ones,
wherever they may be.

1194
01:52:33,496 --> 01:52:38,083
Lord, l know you sees
into the hearts of all men...

1195
01:52:38,251 --> 01:52:41,170
. ..just like you sees into the heart
of old Jim Lewis.

1196
01:52:43,423 --> 01:52:48,677
And, Lord, l know there's
no lying or deceitfulness. . .

1197
01:52:48,845 --> 01:52:50,846
. ..can hide from you.

1198
01:52:51,765 --> 01:52:52,931
You find the truth. ..

1199
01:52:53,099 --> 01:52:59,521
. ..in the bottom of the deepest pit
of darkness.

1200
01:52:59,689 --> 01:53:04,651
There be no hiding from your truth
and your ever-watchful eye.

1201
01:53:05,278 --> 01:53:07,112
Amen.

1202
01:53:07,280 --> 01:53:08,864
How is it, Lord?

1203
01:53:09,949 --> 01:53:14,119
Can you explain something
to this old Virginia man?

1204
01:53:14,788 --> 01:53:19,041
How is it a good Christian man. . .

1205
01:53:19,209 --> 01:53:21,293
. ..like some folks l know...

1206
01:53:21,461 --> 01:53:25,339
. ..can tolerate their black brothers
in bondage?

1207
01:53:26,132 --> 01:53:30,052
How is it, Lord, they don't just...

1208
01:53:30,720 --> 01:53:33,639
. ..break them chains?

1209
01:53:34,808 --> 01:53:37,392
How is it, Lord?

1210
01:53:37,560 --> 01:53:42,064
My heart is open and aching.

1211
01:53:42,232 --> 01:53:44,024
And l wants to know.

1212
01:53:49,739 --> 01:53:51,824
Lord, speak to us.

1213
01:53:51,991 --> 01:53:53,242
Speak to your children.

1214
01:53:53,409 --> 01:53:59,164
Speak to Jim Lewis and Thomas Jackson,
your humble and obedient servants.

1215
01:53:59,332 --> 01:54:01,917
Speak to all of us.

1216
01:54:02,335 --> 01:54:05,170
Our hearts are open.

1217
01:54:05,839 --> 01:54:08,257
Lord, you show us the way,
we will follow.

1218
01:54:13,847 --> 01:54:18,934
Amen.

1219
01:54:25,692 --> 01:54:27,025
[SlGHS]

1220
01:54:30,530 --> 01:54:32,948
-Jim?
-Yeah.

1221
01:54:34,784 --> 01:54:36,660
What is the status of your family?

1222
01:54:37,120 --> 01:54:40,873
About half is free, half slave.

1223
01:54:41,040 --> 01:54:44,877
That's counting all the cousins and such.

1224
01:54:45,545 --> 01:54:48,714
You must know that there are
some officers in this Army. . .

1225
01:54:48,882 --> 01:54:51,383
. ..who are of the opinion that...

1226
01:54:51,551 --> 01:54:55,470
. ..we should be enlisting Negroes
as a condition for freedom.

1227
01:54:56,472 --> 01:54:58,849
That's what they says around the camp.

1228
01:54:59,017 --> 01:55:03,854
Your people will be free,
one way or another.

1229
01:55:04,022 --> 01:55:07,024
The question is,
if the Southern government will have. . .

1230
01:55:07,191 --> 01:55:10,485
. ..the good sense to do it first and soon.

1231
01:55:10,653 --> 01:55:14,531
And in so doing seal a bond
of enduring friendship between us.

1232
01:55:17,493 --> 01:55:20,495
That's what they says, general.

1233
01:55:21,664 --> 01:55:25,000
God's plan is a great mystery.

1234
01:55:25,543 --> 01:55:28,670
lt will be revealed to us.

1235
01:55:37,722 --> 01:55:41,016
That's all the fodder you get tonight.

1236
01:55:41,184 --> 01:55:45,354
We's going to a country where there's
nothing more for an animal to eat...

1237
01:55:45,521 --> 01:55:49,691
. ..than there is what's in the palm
of my hand. Ha, ha.

1238
01:56:01,829 --> 01:56:04,581
General Lee, fine day, sir.

1239
01:56:04,749 --> 01:56:08,752
We got batteries all along that hill,
covering our front to the river.

1240
01:56:08,920 --> 01:56:10,420
Strong anchor on the north.

1241
01:56:10,588 --> 01:56:13,840
Tomorrow, guns will be positioned
in those trees to the south.

1242
01:56:14,092 --> 01:56:18,053
We'll be able to cover the entire
open ground, all of it.

1243
01:56:18,221 --> 01:56:22,766
General, they gonna come at us here?

1244
01:56:22,934 --> 01:56:25,268
Colonel Alexander...

1245
01:56:25,436 --> 01:56:29,481
. ..Federal troops amassed across that river
are watching us prepare for them.

1246
01:56:29,649 --> 01:56:32,317
lf l were General Burnside,
l wouldn't attack here.

1247
01:56:32,485 --> 01:56:35,612
l'd move back upstream,
come across from above us.

1248
01:56:35,780 --> 01:56:38,573
Burnside is not a man
with the luxury of flexibility.

1249
01:56:38,741 --> 01:56:42,119
He's being pushed from behind
by loud voices in Washington. . .

1250
01:56:42,286 --> 01:56:45,747
. ..by newspapers
who demand quick action.

1251
01:56:45,915 --> 01:56:49,251
But we're here,
and so he will attack us here.

1252
01:56:49,419 --> 01:56:52,004
We got batteries pointing from all angles.

1253
01:56:52,171 --> 01:56:54,673
They cross that canal,
that'll slow them down.

1254
01:56:55,258 --> 01:56:57,426
We shall hit them from all sides.

1255
01:56:57,593 --> 01:57:00,470
No, sir, a chicken couldn't live
on that field.

1256
01:57:05,601 --> 01:57:07,227
General Lee, sir.

1257
01:57:07,437 --> 01:57:09,187
General Jackson sends his respects. . .

1258
01:57:09,355 --> 01:57:12,941
. ..and advises his corps will deploy
to the south of this position. . .

1259
01:57:13,109 --> 01:57:14,901
. ..by tomorrow, as you instructed.

1260
01:57:16,154 --> 01:57:18,113
Well, what are his men made of?

1261
01:57:18,281 --> 01:57:20,240
He's 1 50 miles away.

1262
01:57:20,491 --> 01:57:23,160
To General Jackson,
dawn begins the minute after midnight.

1263
01:57:25,788 --> 01:57:29,541
General Hood, l've often wondered
how it is that.. .

1264
01:57:29,709 --> 01:57:34,463
. ..Texas men, the most independent-minded
in this Army of irascibles. . .

1265
01:57:34,630 --> 01:57:37,299
. ..have agreed to serve under
a Kentuckian.

1266
01:57:37,467 --> 01:57:40,469
l have often wondered the same.

1267
01:57:41,220 --> 01:57:46,808
General Gregg, have you settled your
differences with General Jackson?

1268
01:57:47,060 --> 01:57:50,228
No, General Hill, l have not.

1269
01:57:50,730 --> 01:57:52,898
Have you?

1270
01:57:54,400 --> 01:57:56,735
No, sir.

1271
01:57:59,530 --> 01:58:01,573
JACKSON:
Tell me, general...

1272
01:58:02,283 --> 01:58:06,244
. ..do you expect to live
until the end of this war?

1273
01:58:06,621 --> 01:58:11,249
Oh. l do not know. . .

1274
01:58:12,752 --> 01:58:15,087
. ..but l'm inclined to think l will.

1275
01:58:15,254 --> 01:58:17,631
l expect l will be wounded.

1276
01:58:18,841 --> 01:58:21,259
And you, general?

1277
01:58:22,428 --> 01:58:26,681
l do not expect to live to see
the end of this war.

1278
01:58:27,433 --> 01:58:32,354
Nor can l say that without victory
l would desire to do so.

1279
01:58:36,359 --> 01:58:40,028
-Get up.
-Get up.

1280
01:58:47,537 --> 01:58:49,788
Sir?

1281
01:58:50,289 --> 01:58:53,834
Yes, Mr. Pendleton, you may enter.

1282
01:58:54,001 --> 01:58:57,546
Forgive me, general.
There's a letter for you.

1283
01:58:57,713 --> 01:59:03,385
Courier was running a little slow today,
but l thought you'd want to see it.

1284
01:59:04,470 --> 01:59:05,887
Yes, thank you.

1285
01:59:07,056 --> 01:59:09,474
Good night, sir.

1286
01:59:45,261 --> 01:59:47,012
ANNA:
My own dear father:

1287
01:59:48,347 --> 01:59:52,350
As my mother's letter
has been cut short by my arrival...

1288
01:59:52,518 --> 01:59:55,604
...l think it but justice
that I should continue it.

1289
01:59:56,439 --> 01:59:59,608
l know that you are rejoiced
to hear of my coming.

1290
01:59:59,775 --> 02:00:04,029
And l hope that God has sent me
to radiate your pathway through life.

1291
02:00:05,281 --> 02:00:08,116
l am a very tiny little thing.

1292
02:00:08,284 --> 02:00:10,535
l weigh only eight and a half pounds...

1293
02:00:10,703 --> 02:00:16,208
...and Aunt Harriet says l am
the express image of my darling papa.

1294
02:00:16,375 --> 02:00:19,544
My mother is very comfortable
this morning.

1295
02:00:20,463 --> 02:00:24,382
Your loving daughter.

1296
02:00:31,140 --> 02:00:33,725
Thank you, Lord.

1297
02:00:33,893 --> 02:00:36,478
Thank you.

1298
02:00:36,729 --> 02:00:38,563
Thank you, thank you.

1299
02:00:39,232 --> 02:00:42,567
They've occupied all the buildings
along the riverfront.

1300
02:00:42,735 --> 02:00:46,321
We will be lining up those pontoon
bridges through a hail of lead.

1301
02:00:46,822 --> 02:00:50,659
Once across, the Rebs are sure
to make us pay for every block.

1302
02:00:50,826 --> 02:00:54,329
Beyond the town is the canal
which cuts across this open field.. .

1303
02:00:54,497 --> 02:00:58,833
. ..a field we'll have to cross to reach
their entrenchments on Marye's Heights. ..

1304
02:00:59,001 --> 02:01:02,671
. ..another difficult obstacle
in the face of artillery fire.

1305
02:01:02,838 --> 02:01:05,590
Down to our left we could burst through.. .

1306
02:01:05,758 --> 02:01:11,179
. ..turn Jackson's lines, push him back,
trap Longstreet on top of the hill.. .

1307
02:01:11,347 --> 02:01:12,973
. ..surround him.

1308
02:01:15,268 --> 02:01:16,685
lt's possible.

1309
02:01:17,937 --> 02:01:20,939
Turn Jackson's lines?

1310
02:01:21,607 --> 02:01:24,442
No, general, we'll meet them head on.

1311
02:01:24,610 --> 02:01:27,112
And it will be a bloody mess.

1312
02:01:27,280 --> 02:01:29,197
We'll march up to that hill there. ..

1313
02:01:29,365 --> 02:01:34,286
. ..and we'll eat their artillery fire
all the way across this field.

1314
02:01:41,794 --> 02:01:44,713
We'll be able to look
at ourselves and say:

1315
02:01:44,880 --> 02:01:47,716
"We're good soldiers.
We did what we were told."

1316
02:01:47,883 --> 02:01:52,637
lf we're not successful, we can say it was
a good plan, but there were contingencies.

1317
02:01:52,805 --> 02:01:54,723
You can go back to your hometown...

1318
02:01:54,890 --> 02:01:58,977
. ..and tell the families of your men
they died doing their duty.

1319
02:01:59,812 --> 02:02:03,315
The Rebs have fortified
the high ground up the river.

1320
02:02:03,482 --> 02:02:07,736
And anyway, there are strong currents
and obstacles to a crossing there.

1321
02:02:07,903 --> 02:02:10,238
Below Fredericksburg,
the river is too wide.

1322
02:02:10,406 --> 02:02:13,408
And our earliest forces are
clear down to Port Royal.

1323
02:02:13,826 --> 02:02:17,746
Fredericksburg is now
the only place we can cross.

1324
02:02:17,913 --> 02:02:23,501
lf Burnside doesn't cross here,
he might as well resign.

1325
02:02:25,963 --> 02:02:30,842
That wily gray fox has outmaneuvered
our command again.

1326
02:02:31,177 --> 02:02:34,429
And there's going to be hell to pay.

1327
02:03:03,125 --> 02:03:04,501
MAN:
Hurry up! Let's go!

1328
02:03:07,046 --> 02:03:08,630
BARKSDALE:
Pick your targets, boys!

1329
02:03:09,298 --> 02:03:11,174
Commence firing!

1330
02:03:45,501 --> 02:03:46,835
[SOLDlERS SHOUTlNG]

1331
02:03:53,551 --> 02:03:57,762
Them Yankees is coming, sure as Jesus.
They got two pontoons across that river.

1332
02:03:57,930 --> 02:04:00,432
We got to get you and them children
out of here.

1333
02:04:00,599 --> 02:04:04,185
Stop fussing with me. Get your family
ready. We'll leave together.

1334
02:04:04,353 --> 02:04:07,856
Miss Jane, us done talked this over,
and we decided to stay here.. .

1335
02:04:08,023 --> 02:04:10,608
. ..and look after the house.
No use saying no more.

1336
02:04:10,776 --> 02:04:13,945
Martha, l won't leave you to the mercy
of those blue devils.

1337
02:04:14,113 --> 02:04:17,615
Miss Jane, you know they ain't gonna be
bothering us colored folks.

1338
02:04:17,783 --> 02:04:22,287
lf we go with you, there won't be any food
left in the pantry when we come back.

1339
02:04:22,455 --> 02:04:25,039
And we need to eat, same as you.

1340
02:04:27,960 --> 02:04:31,129
-Pastor Lacy, we must run to our lines.
LACY: There's no time.

1341
02:04:31,297 --> 02:04:33,756
The streets are raining iron.
To the basement.

1342
02:04:35,176 --> 02:04:36,426
[SHOUTS]

1343
02:04:50,816 --> 02:04:53,568
Anybody hurt?

1344
02:04:53,736 --> 02:04:55,987
Sam?

1345
02:04:58,741 --> 02:05:00,909
Easy.

1346
02:05:03,496 --> 02:05:05,330
Sam!

1347
02:05:05,498 --> 02:05:08,249
Can you get up? Easy! Easy!

1348
02:05:39,573 --> 02:05:40,949
Fall back, Mississippi!

1349
02:05:42,618 --> 02:05:44,077
Fall back!

1350
02:05:45,663 --> 02:05:47,038
[KNOCKlNG ON DOOR]

1351
02:05:47,790 --> 02:05:49,541
JOHN:
Mother? Are you here?

1352
02:05:49,708 --> 02:05:52,377
Oh, praise be! lt's Master John!

1353
02:05:52,545 --> 02:05:55,922
-We're down here in the cellar!
JOHN: The door is blocked!

1354
02:05:56,382 --> 02:05:59,217
l'll go around to the side!

1355
02:06:03,389 --> 02:06:07,475
Children, y'all stay right here.
Mama'll be back.

1356
02:06:07,851 --> 02:06:10,478
Come out!
There's an ambulance out front.

1357
02:06:10,646 --> 02:06:12,814
The enemy is crossing the river. Hurry!

1358
02:06:33,002 --> 02:06:37,839
-No! Martha, l won't leave without you.
-l done told you, l'm staying.

1359
02:06:38,007 --> 02:06:40,341
Off with you then.

1360
02:06:42,177 --> 02:06:45,096
Come on, Martha.

1361
02:06:45,264 --> 02:06:47,890
Stay in the basement!

1362
02:06:48,559 --> 02:06:49,892
Hyah.

1363
02:08:38,877 --> 02:08:40,128
[SHOUTlNG]

1364
02:08:53,809 --> 02:08:55,476
Get the bayonets!

1365
02:09:40,189 --> 02:09:42,273
May God be with them.

1366
02:09:42,441 --> 02:09:46,944
May he strengthen their hearts
and their arms for the coming struggle.

1367
02:09:47,112 --> 02:09:49,822
Give them the victory.

1368
02:09:53,494 --> 02:09:54,911
[CHATTERlNG]

1369
02:10:04,713 --> 02:10:08,466
Can l be of service
to you fine Northern gentlemen?

1370
02:10:08,634 --> 02:10:10,718
ls this your master's place?

1371
02:10:10,886 --> 02:10:12,386
This is my place.

1372
02:10:15,808 --> 02:10:16,891
Children!

1373
02:10:25,275 --> 02:10:27,151
Sorry to have to bother you, ma'am.

1374
02:10:27,319 --> 02:10:29,821
Come on, let's go.

1375
02:10:31,156 --> 02:10:33,908
Go back inside. Hurry up.

1376
02:10:40,290 --> 02:10:44,460
Put a stop to this at once!
Where are the officers?

1377
02:10:44,628 --> 02:10:48,422
Drop that, soldier. Now!

1378
02:10:49,258 --> 02:10:51,843
Get a message to Couch, to Hancock.

1379
02:10:52,010 --> 02:10:57,223
This will not be tolerated!
This is an army, not a rabble!

1380
02:11:21,498 --> 02:11:26,252
Well, General Jackson,
you are a most gallant sight this morning.

1381
02:11:26,420 --> 02:11:29,964
Thank you, General Stuart,
your gift is much appreciated.

1382
02:11:30,132 --> 02:11:33,384
General Longstreet, show us
where your troops are positioned.

1383
02:11:33,552 --> 02:11:38,556
Yes, sir. We're anchored on the north
by Anderson's division...

1384
02:11:38,724 --> 02:11:41,726
. ..up on the bend in the river
and Ransom's division...

1385
02:11:42,060 --> 02:11:45,229
. ..along and below the ridge
of Marye's Heights...

1386
02:11:45,397 --> 02:11:50,318
. ..with Cobb's brigade dug in down
on the road behind that stone wall.

1387
02:11:50,485 --> 02:11:53,487
Now, to their right, is General McLaws...

1388
02:11:53,655 --> 02:11:58,492
. ..and further down in the woods
and to the right, Pickett and Hood.

1389
02:11:58,660 --> 02:12:00,828
General Hood is my right flank.

1390
02:12:01,580 --> 02:12:06,500
He's connected in those heavy trees
over there with General Jackson's left.

1391
02:12:06,668 --> 02:12:09,754
Up here on the Heights,
we have the Washington artillery. ..

1392
02:12:09,922 --> 02:12:13,090
. ..Colonel Alexander's batteries
and support.

1393
02:12:13,258 --> 02:12:15,384
lt's a strong line, general.

1394
02:12:15,552 --> 02:12:16,594
Very well.

1395
02:12:17,095 --> 02:12:20,014
General Jackson, would you please extend
the line for us?

1396
02:12:20,182 --> 02:12:25,269
Um, General A.P. Hill is on the left,
adjoining General Hood.

1397
02:12:25,437 --> 02:12:28,940
Position is supported by General Taliaferro
and General Early.

1398
02:12:29,107 --> 02:12:32,443
Now to the right flank and behind
is D.H. Hill.

1399
02:12:32,694 --> 02:12:36,030
We've built a road behind our lines
running the entire length.

1400
02:12:36,198 --> 02:12:38,908
We can move troops as is necessary.

1401
02:12:39,076 --> 02:12:42,286
lf the enemy penetrates our lines
at any point...

1402
02:12:42,454 --> 02:12:46,415
. ..the reserves, Taliaferro and Early,
can move rapidly to a new position.

1403
02:12:46,583 --> 02:12:48,834
lf the enemy attempts to cut our center. ..

1404
02:12:49,002 --> 02:12:52,546
. ..or if General Pickett is pressed,
we can change positions, sir.

1405
02:12:53,048 --> 02:12:54,632
Good, very good.

1406
02:12:54,800 --> 02:12:58,636
General Stuart, are you in a strong position
for protecting. . .

1407
02:12:58,804 --> 02:13:00,262
. ..General Jackson's flank?

1408
02:13:00,430 --> 02:13:01,472
STUART:
Oh, yes, sir.

1409
02:13:01,640 --> 02:13:05,226
