2132
03:35:16,278 --> 03:35:17,653
[CHUCKLES]

2133
03:35:27,831 --> 03:35:29,457
He won't agree.

2134
03:35:30,125 --> 03:35:31,250
[SCOFFS]

2135
03:35:34,588 --> 03:35:36,047
Mr. Minnis.

2136
03:35:36,673 --> 03:35:41,260
Would you tell him that you were sent
to take General Lee's photograph. ..

2137
03:35:41,428 --> 03:35:45,932
. ..but that General Lee declined unless
General Jackson's was taken first.

2138
03:35:46,099 --> 03:35:47,683
Certainly, Captain Pendleton.

2139
03:35:57,986 --> 03:36:00,154
No photographs.

2140
03:36:02,240 --> 03:36:07,995
Sir, l was sent from Richmond
to take a photograph of General Lee. ..

2141
03:36:08,163 --> 03:36:12,708
. ..but the general decided that
he did not want his photograph taken. . .

2142
03:36:12,876 --> 03:36:16,545
. ..until l had taken your photograph first.

2143
03:36:16,713 --> 03:36:21,050
Sir, General Lee was most insistent
on the importance of your photograph.

2144
03:36:21,969 --> 03:36:25,262
l cannot refuse General Lee's request.

2145
03:36:35,732 --> 03:36:38,317
Where do you wish me to stand?

2146
03:37:17,899 --> 03:37:21,527
Mr. Booth is here the entire month.

2147
03:37:21,945 --> 03:37:25,031
He's playing in Hamlet,
Katherine and Petruchio...

2148
03:37:25,198 --> 03:37:29,160
...The Merchant of Venice,
Richard llI and Macbeth.

2149
03:37:30,454 --> 03:37:32,288
Which is your favorite, Mr. President?

2150
03:37:32,789 --> 03:37:34,957
l think nothing equals Macbeth.

2151
03:37:35,125 --> 03:37:36,792
l have read it many times.

2152
03:37:37,544 --> 03:37:40,463
-l am curious to see Mr. Booth's rendition.
-lndeed?

2153
03:37:47,804 --> 03:37:51,057
l am told Booth does
the death scene spectacularly.

2154
03:37:51,224 --> 03:37:54,602
Very physical.
Wilder than his brother Edwin.

2155
03:37:54,770 --> 03:37:58,272
That is one reproach l have
of Shakespeare's heroes.

2156
03:37:58,440 --> 03:38:00,441
What reproach is that, dear?

2157
03:38:00,609 --> 03:38:02,902
They all make long speeches
when they are killed.

2158
03:38:03,070 --> 03:38:04,278
[BOTH LAUGHlNG]

2159
03:38:04,446 --> 03:38:06,155
They do indeed.

2160
03:38:08,200 --> 03:38:11,202
ls this a dagger which l see before me. . .

2161
03:38:11,369 --> 03:38:14,663
. ..handle towards my hand?

2162
03:38:14,831 --> 03:38:17,750
Come, let me clutch thee.

2163
03:38:19,252 --> 03:38:22,004
l have thee not, yet l see thee still.

2164
03:38:22,631 --> 03:38:27,593
Art thou not, fatal vision,
sensible to feeling as to sight?

2165
03:38:27,928 --> 03:38:32,223
Or art thou but a dagger of the mind. . .

2166
03:38:34,226 --> 03:38:36,268
. ..a false creation. . .

2167
03:38:36,520 --> 03:38:40,397
. ..proceeding from
the heat-oppressed brain?

2168
03:38:40,565 --> 03:38:42,066
l see thee yet. . .

2169
03:38:42,400 --> 03:38:44,819
. ..in form as palpable as this
which now l draw.

2170
03:38:44,986 --> 03:38:47,446
Thou marshall'st me
the way that l was going. ..

2171
03:38:47,948 --> 03:38:51,700
. ..and such an instrument l was to use.

2172
03:38:53,286 --> 03:38:56,831
Mine eyes are made the fools
o' the other senses.

2173
03:38:57,374 --> 03:38:59,375
l see thee still. . .

2174
03:39:00,377 --> 03:39:04,547
. ..and on thy blade and dudgeon...

2175
03:39:05,382 --> 03:39:09,093
. ..gouts of blood,
which was not so before.

2176
03:39:09,845 --> 03:39:13,848
lt is the bloody business which informs
thus to mine eyes.

2177
03:39:16,059 --> 03:39:18,269
Whiles l threat...

2178
03:39:18,770 --> 03:39:19,937
. ..he lives.

2179
03:39:20,897 --> 03:39:25,276
Words to the heat of deeds too cold
breath gives.

2180
03:39:27,863 --> 03:39:31,907
l go, and it is done.

2181
03:39:33,410 --> 03:39:35,244
The bell invites me.

2182
03:39:37,247 --> 03:39:39,498
Hear it not, Duncan. . .

2183
03:39:40,125 --> 03:39:44,461
. ..for it is a knell
that summons thee to heaven...

2184
03:39:45,714 --> 03:39:47,256
. ..or to hell.

2185
03:39:59,978 --> 03:40:02,438
Well, Mr. Booth, another triumph.

2186
03:40:03,273 --> 03:40:05,900
The president and Mrs. Lincoln
wish to see you.

2187
03:40:06,067 --> 03:40:07,276
[CHUCKLES]

2188
03:40:12,407 --> 03:40:14,617
You may tell that tyrant...

2189
03:40:15,994 --> 03:40:18,078
. ..that destroyer of civil liberties. . .

2190
03:40:18,914 --> 03:40:20,831
. ..that warmonger...

2191
03:40:21,958 --> 03:40:23,459
. ..that l am indisposed. Huh?

2192
03:40:26,796 --> 03:40:29,965
Better still, tell him nothing.

2193
03:40:32,135 --> 03:40:34,470
Tell him l'd already gone.

2194
03:40:45,315 --> 03:40:46,815
Golly gee, Booth.

2195
03:40:48,068 --> 03:40:51,654
An endorsement from
the president of the United States.

2196
03:40:53,490 --> 03:40:55,699
Could be a big thing for your career.

2197
03:41:18,098 --> 03:41:19,765
LEE:
General, from what we've observed. . .

2198
03:41:19,933 --> 03:41:22,685
. ..Hooker has moved five corps,
maybe 70,000 men.

2199
03:41:22,852 --> 03:41:25,312
They're digging in around
Chancellor's mansion.

2200
03:41:25,480 --> 03:41:30,359
Sedgwick has another 40,000
spread out along the Stafford Heights. . .

2201
03:41:30,527 --> 03:41:34,822
. ..on the north bank of the Rappahannock
in front of General Early at Fredericksburg.

2202
03:41:34,990 --> 03:41:39,451
Now, there's possibly 30,000 more
back along the river north of here. . .

2203
03:41:39,619 --> 03:41:41,245
. ..that we've not yet located.

2204
03:41:42,497 --> 03:41:44,623
We're not in a position of strength here.

2205
03:41:44,791 --> 03:41:48,502
We owe a great deal to the unexplainable,
the mystery of General Hooker. . .

2206
03:41:48,670 --> 03:41:51,046
. ..who's allowed us to maneuver freely...

2207
03:41:51,214 --> 03:41:56,593
. ..between two parts of an army
that's more than twice our strength.

2208
03:41:57,178 --> 03:42:00,639
We do not yet understand his plan.

2209
03:42:00,807 --> 03:42:03,100
He may still plan a move
toward Gordonsville. . .

2210
03:42:03,268 --> 03:42:05,602
. ..move around below us,
cut us off from Richmond.

2211
03:42:05,895 --> 03:42:08,397
And there's still Sedgwick on the river.

2212
03:42:08,732 --> 03:42:13,110
Now Sedgwick shows no signs of moving,
but that could change.

2213
03:42:13,486 --> 03:42:15,237
They're anchored against the river. . .

2214
03:42:15,405 --> 03:42:18,741
. ..and their lines continue
down below Chancellorsville. . .

2215
03:42:18,908 --> 03:42:20,993
. ..then curves along here.

2216
03:42:21,202 --> 03:42:24,580
We've observed their lines curving out
in these open clearings. . .

2217
03:42:24,748 --> 03:42:27,750
. ..then extending on out to the west.

2218
03:42:27,917 --> 03:42:31,503
Then what, general?
Do you know where their right flank is?

2219
03:42:31,671 --> 03:42:35,007
JACKSON: No. Not yet.
LEE: We must know. We must know.

2220
03:42:35,175 --> 03:42:38,677
lf he marches in that direction,
he could threaten our flank.. .

2221
03:42:38,845 --> 03:42:43,182
. ..or be going toward Gordonsville
before we can react.

2222
03:42:46,644 --> 03:42:49,271
Out here, in the west,
along this turnpike, here...

2223
03:42:49,439 --> 03:42:54,151
. ..their right flank's in the air.
lt's the one place they're not digging in.

2224
03:42:54,319 --> 03:42:56,737
They're not expecting any pressure there.

2225
03:42:57,238 --> 03:43:01,658
-Who's on their flank?
-1 1 th Corps. Oliver Howard.

2226
03:43:01,826 --> 03:43:06,538
Mm-hm. Were there any roads
farther down below the turnpike?

2227
03:43:06,706 --> 03:43:09,500
Yes, sir. lndeed there are, good roads.

2228
03:43:09,667 --> 03:43:13,087
That's Catherine's Furnace here
and there's a road here.

2229
03:43:13,254 --> 03:43:16,507
-There's a road over this way.
-Then, we must hit them there.

2230
03:43:16,674 --> 03:43:19,968
Then attack the flank.
They will have nowhere to go.

2231
03:43:20,136 --> 03:43:23,889
They'll have to go back across the river
or we will destroy them.

2232
03:43:24,057 --> 03:43:27,643
We're too close to their lines.
They'll observe our movements.

2233
03:43:27,811 --> 03:43:30,145
There must be another road farther down.

2234
03:43:30,980 --> 03:43:33,148
Now, is there someone we know?

2235
03:43:33,316 --> 03:43:36,276
Someone we can trust who knows the area?

2236
03:43:36,694 --> 03:43:39,071
Captain Pendleton.
Find Reverend Lacy for me.

2237
03:43:39,239 --> 03:43:41,323
LACY:
l'm, uh, here, sir.

2238
03:43:41,491 --> 03:43:43,784
This is my chaplain,
the Reverend Tucker Lacy.

2239
03:43:43,952 --> 03:43:45,994
He has family in this area.

2240
03:43:46,162 --> 03:43:48,205
General Lee.

2241
03:43:49,332 --> 03:43:52,918
Reverend, it would be very helpful
if you could find us a safe route...

2242
03:43:53,086 --> 03:43:57,548
-. . .around the enemy.
-Well, sir, uh, there, l know a family.

2243
03:43:57,715 --> 03:44:02,261
The Wellfords. Uh, l suggest a visit to them.
We may find ourselves a guide.

2244
03:44:02,429 --> 03:44:06,974
Please go at once, Mr. Lacy. Find someone
who might show us how we might proceed.

2245
03:44:07,142 --> 03:44:08,851
Yes, sir.

2246
03:44:10,895 --> 03:44:15,691
Then it has been decided, general.
This mission will be yours.

2247
03:44:18,153 --> 03:44:20,612
l would not have it any other way.

2248
03:44:33,042 --> 03:44:35,377
Where is General Jackson, Jim?

2249
03:44:36,880 --> 03:44:39,339
He done gone to see his officers, sir.

2250
03:44:43,303 --> 03:44:48,557
How come that you know so much
about what the general is thinking, Jim?

2251
03:44:49,392 --> 03:44:50,851
None of us do.

2252
03:44:51,019 --> 03:44:54,354
The general never tells me nothing, sir.

2253
03:44:54,522 --> 03:44:57,608
But the way l knows is this:

2254
03:44:57,775 --> 03:45:01,445
The general say his prayers twice a day...

2255
03:45:01,613 --> 03:45:03,489
. ..morning and night.

2256
03:45:03,656 --> 03:45:08,243
But if he gets out of bed in the night
two or three times to pray...

2257
03:45:08,411 --> 03:45:11,163
. .. l just packs the haversack.

2258
03:45:11,331 --> 03:45:15,584
l know there's a move on hand
and hell to pay in the morning.

2259
03:45:15,793 --> 03:45:17,377
[LAUGH lNG]

2260
03:45:18,087 --> 03:45:20,255
"Hell to pay in the morning."

2261
03:45:20,798 --> 03:45:22,049
Very amusing.

2262
03:45:22,634 --> 03:45:24,593
-Amusing.
-Yeah.

2263
03:45:26,095 --> 03:45:27,429
Yeah.

2264
03:45:28,640 --> 03:45:30,098
Wait.

2265
03:45:34,103 --> 03:45:36,146
There is another road.

2266
03:45:39,442 --> 03:45:42,319
lt's a road that runs
well below the Federal lines.

2267
03:45:42,487 --> 03:45:45,656
The Wellford boy explained it to me.
He knows the route.

2268
03:45:45,990 --> 03:45:49,201
He will march with us to where
this road rejoins the turnpike. . .

2269
03:45:49,369 --> 03:45:51,995
. ..then we turn to the east
and attack their right flank.

2270
03:45:52,497 --> 03:45:56,959
lt is a greater distance, perhaps 1 2 or
1 3 miles, but the boys can do it.

2271
03:45:57,126 --> 03:45:58,502
They have never let us down.

2272
03:46:02,757 --> 03:46:04,466
Farewell, general.

2273
03:46:05,426 --> 03:46:07,553
How many troops will you require?

2274
03:46:08,471 --> 03:46:10,222
Five, general, my whole corps.

2275
03:46:11,599 --> 03:46:13,642
And what will you leave me?

2276
03:46:13,977 --> 03:46:17,729
Well, the divisions
of Anderson and McLaws.

2277
03:46:18,982 --> 03:46:23,360
You leave me 1 2,000 men
against Hooker's 70,000.

2278
03:46:24,070 --> 03:46:26,321
lf Hooker pushes out of his trenches.. .

2279
03:46:26,489 --> 03:46:30,158
. ..he could destroy not only the plan
but possibly the Army.

2280
03:46:30,952 --> 03:46:33,829
And there's still Sedgwick
along the river.

2281
03:46:33,997 --> 03:46:38,292
How long will he sit staring at Marye's Hill?
How long?

2282
03:46:42,130 --> 03:46:45,048
We've divided the Army before.

2283
03:46:46,551 --> 03:46:51,096
We must retain the advantage of
surprise, we must outflank the flankers.

2284
03:46:51,264 --> 03:46:54,683
We must beat them at their own game.

2285
03:46:57,145 --> 03:47:03,275
Take your entire corps,
General Jackson, and destroy the enemy.

2286
03:47:05,028 --> 03:47:07,112
God be with you.

2287
03:47:23,546 --> 03:47:25,839
Boys, my days are numbered.

2288
03:47:26,758 --> 03:47:28,592
My time has come.

2289
03:47:30,011 --> 03:47:34,806
You can laugh, but my time has come.

2290
03:47:37,769 --> 03:47:41,772
l got a 20-dollar gold piece l carried
through the war and a silver watch. . .

2291
03:47:41,939 --> 03:47:44,483
. ..my daddy sent to me
through the lines.

2292
03:47:48,279 --> 03:47:50,572
Take them off of me when l'm dead.

2293
03:47:51,949 --> 03:47:55,577
Give them to my captain to give to my
daddy when he gets back home.

2294
03:47:55,745 --> 03:47:59,289
Here's my clothes and my blanket.
Anybody who wishes can have them.

2295
03:48:01,000 --> 03:48:06,797
My rations l do not wish at all. My gun
and cartridge box l expect to die with.

2296
03:48:17,392 --> 03:48:18,934
-Mr. Smith.
-Sir.

2297
03:48:19,102 --> 03:48:23,105
Your instructions to the ranks: There is
to be no noise, l want no talking.

2298
03:48:23,272 --> 03:48:25,816
Stragglers will be bayoneted,
let the men know.

2299
03:48:25,983 --> 03:48:30,445
No muskets are to be loaded until we
deploy for battle. Secrecy, Mr. Smith.

2300
03:48:30,613 --> 03:48:33,198
Everything depends upon
the element of surprise.

2301
03:48:33,366 --> 03:48:37,202
Sir, l'll convey the orders. No stragglers.

2302
03:48:41,499 --> 03:48:44,710
-Reverend.
-May we bow our heads.

2303
03:48:46,462 --> 03:48:51,216
Dear Lord, heavenly Father,
you who know all things.

2304
03:48:51,384 --> 03:48:54,845
We face again a mighty
foe, a vast host.

2305
03:48:55,304 --> 03:48:58,223
An enemy more than twice our number.

2306
03:48:58,391 --> 03:49:02,978
But you have taught us
to fear not, to trust in you.

2307
03:49:03,312 --> 03:49:08,316
When the Philistines came before them,
the people of lsrael feared Goliath.

2308
03:49:08,484 --> 03:49:10,318
Their Army was in terror.

2309
03:49:10,486 --> 03:49:14,448
No one had the courage to stand
against the mighty warrior.

2310
03:49:14,615 --> 03:49:18,660
Then you brought forth David,
a mere boy.

2311
03:49:18,828 --> 03:49:21,788
And Saul armed David with his armor...

2312
03:49:21,956 --> 03:49:25,959
...and he put a helmet
of brass upon his head.

2313
03:49:26,127 --> 03:49:29,337
Also he armed him with a coat of mail.

2314
03:49:29,505 --> 03:49:35,761
And DaVid girded his sword upon
his armor and he assayed to go.

2315
03:50:01,245 --> 03:50:06,208
General Rodes, deploy your men on
either side of the turnpike, brigade front.

2316
03:50:06,375 --> 03:50:08,627
How soon will
General Colston's men be up?

2317
03:50:08,795 --> 03:50:10,921
We're right behind, general.

2318
03:50:15,802 --> 03:50:17,219
JACKSON:
General Lee...

2319
03:50:18,763 --> 03:50:21,765
...l hope as soon as
practicable to attack...

2320
03:50:21,933 --> 03:50:27,229
...l trust that an ever kind providence
will bless us with great success.

2321
03:50:31,526 --> 03:50:33,819
Take this to General Lee.

2322
03:50:36,781 --> 03:50:39,783
Well, General Rodes...

2323
03:50:41,953 --> 03:50:46,206
. ..it appears the Virginia Military
lnstitute will be heard from today.

2324
03:50:47,416 --> 03:50:49,292
Deploy your brigade.

2325
03:53:05,054 --> 03:53:09,557
Two hours of daylight left.
Are you ready, General Rodes?

2326
03:53:10,017 --> 03:53:11,977
You may move forward.

2327
03:55:27,905 --> 03:55:29,531
[ALL SHOUTlNG]

2328
03:55:38,207 --> 03:55:39,916
SOLDlER 1 :
Fall back!

2329
03:55:40,084 --> 03:55:42,252
SOLDlER 2:
They're coming! Get your muskets!

2330
03:56:01,230 --> 03:56:04,774
-Shoulder to shoulder! Let's go, let's go!
-Fall back!

2331
03:56:05,860 --> 03:56:08,278
Aim, fire!

2332
03:56:08,445 --> 03:56:09,904
Pull back and save yourself!

2333
03:56:46,400 --> 03:56:50,111
Fall back!

2334
03:56:50,279 --> 03:56:52,780
Fire! Fall back!

2335
03:56:53,115 --> 03:56:56,576
lnto the trees, men! Fall back!

2336
03:57:09,465 --> 03:57:10,965
SOLDlER 3:
lnto the trees!

2337
03:57:30,361 --> 03:57:32,946
Form a line! Form a line!

2338
03:57:33,113 --> 03:57:34,822
Form a line!

2339
03:57:35,491 --> 03:57:37,075
-Run! Run!
-Charge!

2340
03:58:21,620 --> 03:58:23,246
Press on!

2341
03:58:29,545 --> 03:58:34,007
Hold up right here! Aim! Fire!

2342
03:59:05,706 --> 03:59:10,335
Push on!

2343
03:59:18,177 --> 03:59:35,151
Fire!

2344
04:00:15,275 --> 04:00:18,736
Hell, that's hot. l knew
you'd be all right, you dang fool.

2345
04:00:25,744 --> 04:00:26,994
Oh, God.

2346
04:00:42,719 --> 04:00:44,137
Regroup!

2347
04:00:44,638 --> 04:00:47,515
-Stop running!
-Move into line!

2348
04:00:47,683 --> 04:00:49,350
Stay together!

2349
04:00:49,893 --> 04:00:52,603
My God! Give them the bayonet!

2350
04:00:54,773 --> 04:00:57,233
-Stop running!
-Stop running!

2351
04:00:57,401 --> 04:00:59,444
Stop running, soldier!

2352
04:00:59,611 --> 04:01:04,282
Stop running! Rally with me, men!

2353
04:01:05,617 --> 04:01:08,578
-Rally with me!
-Stop! Rally around the general!

2354
04:01:10,581 --> 04:01:14,292
We have stopped, sir. Can't see.
The lines are tangled.

2355
04:01:14,460 --> 04:01:17,795
We're mixed in with Rodes' men.
lt's confusion, sir.

2356
04:01:17,963 --> 04:01:20,882
We need Hill to come up.
Hill's men can move on by us.

2357
04:01:21,049 --> 04:01:23,551
Tell General Colston
he must re-form his men.

2358
04:01:23,719 --> 04:01:27,513
Now l will strongly urge General Hill
to push forward hard.

2359
04:01:27,681 --> 04:01:32,685
We must not stop. Let General Colston
know they will run if we press them.

2360
04:01:32,853 --> 04:01:34,562
Yes, sir.

2361
04:01:35,230 --> 04:01:39,567
General Hill, you must keep the men
moving. We must keep the pressure up.

2362
04:01:39,735 --> 04:01:43,571
We have broken their flank. We can
crush them now if we can cut them off.

2363
04:01:43,739 --> 04:01:46,199
We must not give them time
to get organized.

2364
04:01:46,366 --> 04:01:48,576
General, take your division forward.

2365
04:01:48,744 --> 04:01:52,580
Press on north, move toward the river,
toward the United States ford.

2366
04:01:52,748 --> 04:01:56,083
-We must not let them escape.
-lt's late in the day, general.

2367
04:01:56,251 --> 04:01:59,128
-We don't know the ground.
-Boswell!

2368
04:01:59,296 --> 04:02:04,091
You will ride with General Hill. You will find
a way through the woods to the northeast.

2369
04:02:04,259 --> 04:02:06,928
You will find the rear
of the enemy's position.

2370
04:02:07,095 --> 04:02:08,721
Yes, sir.

2371
04:02:08,889 --> 04:02:11,432
We will cut them off, general!

2372
04:02:58,313 --> 04:03:01,440
They're digging in. Must be Federal.

2373
04:03:04,736 --> 04:03:08,239
Sound carries at night,
they could be a ways off.

2374
04:03:12,494 --> 04:03:17,081
General, sir, we are beyond our lines.
This is no place for you, sir.

2375
04:03:21,128 --> 04:03:22,628
You're right.

2376
04:03:26,258 --> 04:03:28,843
lt cannot go the way l'd hoped.

2377
04:03:30,762 --> 04:03:32,972
lt will have to be tomorrow.

2378
04:03:35,684 --> 04:03:38,352
Gentlemen, let us return to the road.

2379
04:04:01,918 --> 04:04:04,211
Stop firing! You're firing
at your own men!

2380
04:04:05,213 --> 04:04:06,464
Hold it!

2381
04:04:08,383 --> 04:04:10,926
Hold your fire!
These are your own men here!

2382
04:04:11,386 --> 04:04:13,846
lt's a lie! Pour into them, boys!

2383
04:04:16,391 --> 04:04:19,018
Cease fire! Cease fire!

2384
04:04:19,478 --> 04:04:22,688
General Hill, they're our men!

2385
04:04:28,820 --> 04:04:30,780
What have they done?

2386
04:04:34,826 --> 04:04:36,285
Who is this?

2387
04:04:38,288 --> 04:04:41,749
Oh, God, general! Are you hurt badly?

2388
04:04:41,917 --> 04:04:45,461
l'm afraid l am, in my shoulder.

2389
04:04:46,129 --> 04:04:49,340
And here.

2390
04:04:50,425 --> 04:04:54,970
-Get a litter. We need a litter. Move!
SOLDlER: Yes, sir.

2391
04:04:55,430 --> 04:05:00,101
-We must leave here, general.
-Here, take this. lt'll help, sir.

2392
04:05:05,816 --> 04:05:09,026
l will try to keep this from
the knowledge of the troops.

2393
04:05:09,194 --> 04:05:11,946
Thank you, general.

2394
04:05:13,573 --> 04:05:18,285
The Yankees have set up a battery not a
hundred yards. We must get away!

2395
04:05:25,127 --> 04:05:28,963
Ready? Lift! Careful now.

2396
04:05:31,800 --> 04:05:34,385
Move out. Ready, lift.

2397
04:05:56,408 --> 04:06:04,415
Fire!

2398
04:06:07,002 --> 04:06:12,173
General. Lie quiet, or you
will most certainly be killed.

2399
04:06:25,896 --> 04:06:26,937
Let's go. Lift!

2400
04:06:30,192 --> 04:06:33,110
Move! Ready? Lift!

2401
04:06:52,589 --> 04:06:56,759
Doctor, good to see you.

2402
04:06:58,386 --> 04:07:02,389
l am hurt badly.

2403
04:07:03,517 --> 04:07:07,394
l fear l am dying.

2404
04:07:10,524 --> 04:07:14,610
Sir, l want you to drink this.

2405
04:07:15,946 --> 04:07:18,405
lt's whiskey and morphine.

2406
04:07:23,870 --> 04:07:29,500
Your right hand is minor.
The ball lodged under the skin.

2407
04:07:30,919 --> 04:07:32,920
lt's these other wounds.

2408
04:07:34,798 --> 04:07:38,133
l need to examine your arm.

2409
04:07:38,301 --> 04:07:42,388
And l'll administer chloroform
to make it painless.

2410
04:07:43,473 --> 04:07:48,143
lf l should find that the condition
warrants amputation...

2411
04:07:48,603 --> 04:07:51,105
. ..may l proceed at once?

2412
04:07:54,776 --> 04:07:59,238
l have complete faith
in you, Dr. McGuire.

2413
04:08:00,490 --> 04:08:04,577
You must do to me whatever
you think necessary.

2414
04:08:14,296 --> 04:08:16,630
Breathe deeply, general.

2415
04:08:23,972 --> 04:08:26,932
What an infinite blessing.

2416
04:08:36,526 --> 04:08:38,736
Blessing.

2417
04:08:43,783 --> 04:08:45,451
[ALL CHEERlNG]

2418
04:09:04,512 --> 04:09:08,390
Doesn't seem right that General Jackson
isn't here to see this.

2419
04:09:08,892 --> 04:09:15,189
No, major. lt does not seem right at all.
But it is the will of God.

2420
04:09:17,233 --> 04:09:22,404
He's lost his left arm. l've lost my right.

2421
04:09:42,759 --> 04:09:44,176
General?

2422
04:09:46,596 --> 04:09:48,514
How you feeling, sir?

2423
04:09:49,224 --> 04:09:52,893
Do not concern yourself about me.

2424
04:09:53,478 --> 04:09:56,730
But tell me, how are we faring?

2425
04:09:56,898 --> 04:10:01,110
General, the enemy's gone
across the river.

2426
04:10:01,277 --> 04:10:04,571
We secured the high ground
around Chancellorsville.

2427
04:10:04,948 --> 04:10:07,741
General Stuart did well by you, sir.

2428
04:10:09,077 --> 04:10:11,286
And the Stonewall brigade...

2429
04:10:14,082 --> 04:10:19,253
. ..right in the middle of it, sir.
"Remember Jackson," they shouted.

2430
04:10:19,713 --> 04:10:21,839
l heard that all day.

2431
04:10:23,049 --> 04:10:25,676
They were fighting for Stonewall.

2432
04:10:30,515 --> 04:10:36,186
Well, isn't that just like them.
They are a noble set of men.

2433
04:10:36,855 --> 04:10:41,233
That name, Stonewall, belongs
to the brigade, not to me.

2434
04:10:42,944 --> 04:10:44,737
l have the ball.

2435
04:10:47,323 --> 04:10:52,119
Dr. McGuire allowed me to keep the
musket ball he took from your hand.

2436
04:10:54,622 --> 04:10:59,960
lt was a round, smooth bore.
lt had to be one of ours.

2437
04:11:00,545 --> 04:11:05,257
l heard. They thought l was asleep.

2438
04:11:06,384 --> 04:11:10,971
lt could not be helped.
There's no blame in war.

2439
04:11:12,640 --> 04:11:14,933
We must all forgive.

2440
04:11:38,583 --> 04:11:39,958
Watch your step.

2441
04:11:41,044 --> 04:11:42,669
Mrs. Jackson.

2442
04:11:56,184 --> 04:11:57,684
So am--?

2443
04:11:57,852 --> 04:12:01,522
Am l allowed to visit my husband
before he is buried?

2444
04:12:01,689 --> 04:12:02,815
Buried? He's--

2445
04:12:02,982 --> 04:12:05,734
Oh, my. No, no, no.
This is the body of Frank Paxton.

2446
04:12:05,902 --> 04:12:10,239
General Paxton is moving his body
back to Lexington.

2447
04:12:10,406 --> 04:12:13,826
Well, l knew Mr. Paxton.
General Paxton, he's our neighbor.

2448
04:12:13,993 --> 04:12:15,869
His wife, she cried when he left.

2449
04:12:16,037 --> 04:12:19,206
l suppose she knew
something like this would happen.

2450
04:12:20,333 --> 04:12:21,750
Thank you.

2451
04:12:23,128 --> 04:12:29,424
l had to remove your husband's
left arm, patch his right hand.

2452
04:12:30,051 --> 04:12:33,846
He's healing well, l'm very pleased.
But there is a new problem.

2453
04:12:34,013 --> 04:12:36,974
l do believe he is developing pneumonia.

2454
04:12:37,142 --> 04:12:41,145
-May l see him, doctor?
-Well, certainly, certainly. Um, he's weak.

2455
04:12:41,312 --> 04:12:44,815
l've given him some medicine
to help him sleep.

2456
04:12:44,983 --> 04:12:51,113
He's in some pain and the medication
makes him drift away. He's in and out.

2457
04:13:04,335 --> 04:13:05,878
[KNOCKlNG ON DOOR]

2458
04:13:07,297 --> 04:13:13,218
General, l have a treat for you.
Something you may have been missing.

2459
04:13:13,553 --> 04:13:16,555
Another medicine?

2460
04:13:18,892 --> 04:13:21,018
Very well, doctor.

2461
04:13:21,519 --> 04:13:25,939
No, it's not mine, actually.

2462
04:13:26,107 --> 04:13:30,110
But it may do you some good.

2463
04:13:37,493 --> 04:13:43,123
Oh, oh, oh, so sweet. Too much sugar.

2464
04:13:43,291 --> 04:13:47,836
Always the problem with
my esposita's lemonade.

2465
04:14:09,609 --> 04:14:15,948
l'm so glad to see you looking so bright.

2466
04:14:20,036 --> 04:14:23,705
No, no. You must be cheerful.

2467
04:14:25,833 --> 04:14:27,334
Let's not have a long face.

2468
04:14:27,502 --> 04:14:32,839
You know l like cheerfulness
and brightness in a sickroom.

2469
04:14:39,430 --> 04:14:41,265
Esposita.

2470
04:14:42,308 --> 04:14:44,559
My esposita.

2471
04:14:47,897 --> 04:14:51,775
l know you would gladly
give your life for me. . .

2472
04:14:51,943 --> 04:14:57,656
. ..but l am perfectly resigned.
Do not be sad.

2473
04:14:58,950 --> 04:15:01,910
l hope l may yet recover.

2474
04:15:06,040 --> 04:15:07,874
Pray for me.

2475
04:15:09,210 --> 04:15:15,590
But in your prayers, never forget to
use the petition, "Thy will be done."

2476
04:15:29,689 --> 04:15:33,984
l'm so glad you're here.
Your lemonade is delicious.

2477
04:15:34,152 --> 04:15:35,402
[CHUCKLES]

2478
04:15:36,279 --> 04:15:38,739
-lt's not too sweet.
-Too much sugar.

2479
04:15:38,906 --> 04:15:41,575
l never told you that.

2480
04:15:43,828 --> 04:15:48,373
MAN: O, Caesar--
-Hence! Wilt thou lift up Olympus?

2481
04:15:48,541 --> 04:15:49,875
Great Caesar--

2482
04:15:50,335 --> 04:15:53,587
Doth not Brutus bootless kneel?

2483
04:15:54,213 --> 04:15:56,548
Speak, hands, for me!

2484
04:15:57,884 --> 04:15:59,092
[GROANlNG]

2485
04:16:09,729 --> 04:16:11,938
Et tu, Brute!

2486
04:16:13,316 --> 04:16:14,649
[CROWD GASPlNG]

2487
04:16:15,777 --> 04:16:18,570
Then fall, Caesar.

2488
04:16:20,948 --> 04:16:23,825
Liberty! Freedom!

2489
04:16:25,244 --> 04:16:26,953
Tyranny is dead!

2490
04:16:31,584 --> 04:16:33,126
-Hello, Mrs. Chamberlain.
-Hello.

2491
04:16:33,294 --> 04:16:35,295
-Thank you for staying.
-Thank you.

2492
04:16:35,463 --> 04:16:37,297
Come, you must meet the other actors.

2493
04:16:37,465 --> 04:16:43,303
Mr. Harrison, Mr. Booth, may l present
Colonel Chamberlain and his wife.

2494
04:16:44,555 --> 04:16:49,142
May l congratulate you, all of you,
on a most moving interpretation.

2495
04:16:49,477 --> 04:16:51,645
This is only a play.

2496
04:16:51,813 --> 04:16:53,438
We've heard about you, colonel. . .

2497
04:16:53,606 --> 04:16:57,609
. ..and how you stood on the bridge
of the Rappahannock like Horatius. . .

2498
04:16:57,777 --> 04:17:00,821
. ..as hundreds fled in panic round you.

2499
04:17:01,114 --> 04:17:05,992
How can our playing compare to what
you have seen, what you have done?

2500
04:17:06,661 --> 04:17:09,830
Well, remember, gentlemen,
l am not a soldier by nature.

2501
04:17:09,997 --> 04:17:12,124
l am a teacher of rhetoric...

2502
04:17:12,375 --> 04:17:15,669
. ..and my master, as yours,
is Shakespeare.

2503
04:17:16,003 --> 04:17:18,839
And, uh, did you enjoy the play,
Mrs. Chamberlain?

2504
04:17:19,006 --> 04:17:21,174
Oh. Very much.

2505
04:17:21,509 --> 04:17:23,760
Mr. Booth, tell me something.

2506
04:17:23,928 --> 04:17:28,682
Do you regard yourself as the hero
or the villain of Shakespeare's play?

2507
04:17:30,184 --> 04:17:31,852
Well, ha, ha. . . .

2508
04:17:33,771 --> 04:17:38,024
Well, an actor must always regard himself
as a hero, Mrs. Chamberlain...

2509
04:17:38,192 --> 04:17:42,028
. ..even if that role be no more than
a simple soldier who only speaks one line.

2510
04:17:42,280 --> 04:17:48,034
Yes. lt's for the audience to decide
who is a hero and who is villain.

2511
04:17:48,411 --> 04:17:51,037
We merely play the parts allotted to us.

2512
04:17:52,081 --> 04:17:54,207
How do you think of us,
Mrs. Chamberlain...

2513
04:17:54,375 --> 04:17:57,419
. ..Cinna and Brutus,
as heroes or villains?

2514
04:17:58,337 --> 04:17:59,838
Well. . .

2515
04:18:00,548 --> 04:18:03,216
. ..noblest Roman of them all. . .

2516
04:18:03,384 --> 04:18:06,845
. ..you cannot be villains
in Shakespeare's eyes. . .

2517
04:18:07,013 --> 04:18:10,140
. ..though Dante makes you
the worst villains in the world. . .

2518
04:18:10,308 --> 04:18:11,558
. ..after Judas lscariot.

2519
04:18:12,351 --> 04:18:15,228
No, you are not villains to Shakespeare. . .

2520
04:18:15,813 --> 04:18:17,731
. ..but l wonder, are you heroes?

2521
04:18:19,400 --> 04:18:21,943
-Oh. l speak too much. l'm sorry.
-No, no, no.

2522
04:18:22,111 --> 04:18:25,405
My beloved husband has been given
a few days' furlough here. . .

2523
04:18:25,573 --> 04:18:28,450
. ..and everything about these days
delights me utterly.

2524
04:18:28,618 --> 04:18:32,078
Do not expect me to speak intelligently
about your play or anything else.

2525
04:18:32,997 --> 04:18:38,752
My eyes, my heart, my whole being
is dancing uncontrollably with joy. ..

2526
04:18:38,920 --> 04:18:41,838
. ..at being together
with the man that l love.

2527
04:18:42,590 --> 04:18:46,426
Thank you for enriching my stay here
with those immortal words. Thank you.

2528
04:18:47,261 --> 04:18:51,181
Come, Fanny. We must leave the players
to rest after their exertions.

2529
04:18:51,349 --> 04:18:52,599
Good evening.

2530
04:18:55,311 --> 04:18:58,188
What a Caesar, Harrison.

2531
04:18:58,814 --> 04:19:00,690
What a Caesar.

2532
04:19:01,150 --> 04:19:04,236
Too young for Caesar. Henry V.

2533
04:19:04,779 --> 04:19:06,655
Yes, Henry V.

2534
04:19:06,822 --> 04:19:10,534
With that voice shouting,
"Once more into the breach!"

2535
04:19:10,701 --> 04:19:14,538
Oh, yes. Henry V.

2536
04:19:21,963 --> 04:19:24,172
Teacher, not a soldier.

2537
04:19:24,590 --> 04:19:27,008
And a better actor than either of us.

2538
04:19:27,510 --> 04:19:30,679
But he's chosen the right role
in the right play.

2539
04:19:31,264 --> 04:19:33,807
He'll be applauded
long after we're forgotten.

2540
04:19:33,975 --> 04:19:38,478
All we can do, Harrison,
is like l said to Mrs. Chamberlain.

2541
04:19:38,646 --> 04:19:43,149
All we can do is play the roles
allotted to us.

2542
04:19:43,401 --> 04:19:47,487
Well, if a teacher of rhetoric can
become a soldier, so can an actor.

2543
04:19:51,534 --> 04:19:55,495
l've known for some time
l could not go on like this.

2544
04:19:56,414 --> 04:19:57,998
And now. ...

2545
04:20:00,459 --> 04:20:03,003
lf the Yankee cause can sway
a man like that.. .

2546
04:20:03,170 --> 04:20:06,006
. ..then we need every man
we can muster.

2547
04:20:06,173 --> 04:20:08,675
Booth, l'm quitting the stage.
l have to go.

2548
04:20:09,385 --> 04:20:12,178
l loathe, l detest his cause.

2549
04:20:13,180 --> 04:20:16,016
But were l to be killed
by a man like that. . .

2550
04:20:18,436 --> 04:20:19,853
. .. l'd regard it an honor.

2551
04:20:21,314 --> 04:20:25,150
Yes, sir.

2552
04:20:26,444 --> 04:20:27,819
An honor.

2553
04:20:30,072 --> 04:20:33,325
You were always inclined
to melodrama, Harrison.

2554
04:20:34,535 --> 04:20:39,289
What makes you think you'll be
a better soldier than an actor?

2555
04:20:40,499 --> 04:20:42,208
Stay here.

2556
04:20:43,711 --> 04:20:45,503
Your place is here.

2557
04:20:45,838 --> 04:20:49,257
Why should we think what we do
is any less than what soldiers do?

2558
04:20:50,134 --> 04:20:51,885
We may be mere actors.. .

2559
04:20:52,595 --> 04:20:55,889
. ..but think of the words
we help to keep alive.

2560
04:21:00,227 --> 04:21:02,896
Who will remember the names of.. .

2561
04:21:03,481 --> 04:21:07,776
. ..Queen Elizabeth's generals,
and politicians?

2562
04:21:10,071 --> 04:21:11,321
Who will ever forget. . .

2563
04:21:12,198 --> 04:21:13,990
. ..the name...

2564
04:21:15,368 --> 04:21:16,951
. ..Shakespeare?

2565
04:21:25,670 --> 04:21:31,800
ls that my sweet darling angel?

2566
04:21:33,177 --> 04:21:34,344
[JULlA BABBLlNG]

2567
04:21:35,054 --> 04:21:37,263
My Julia.

2568
04:22:01,789 --> 04:22:04,207
ls it certain, doctor?

2569
04:22:05,376 --> 04:22:06,668
[SlGHS]

2570
04:22:08,129 --> 04:22:09,754
Does he know?

2571
04:22:12,049 --> 04:22:13,800
l have not told him.

2572
04:22:15,636 --> 04:22:17,137
Then l will.

2573
04:22:17,972 --> 04:22:19,806
He must know.

2574
04:22:20,933 --> 04:22:23,309
He must be prepared.

2575
04:22:23,477 --> 04:22:26,980
JOSEPH & ANNA [SlNGlNG]:
Guard us, guide us

2576
04:22:27,148 --> 04:22:30,942
Keep us, feed us

2577
04:22:31,110 --> 04:22:37,532
For we have no help but thee

2578
04:22:38,367 --> 04:22:45,373
Yet possessing every blessing

2579
04:22:46,417 --> 04:22:53,423
lf our God our father be

2580
04:23:16,197 --> 04:23:18,239
My darling...

2581
04:23:21,368 --> 04:23:24,245
. ..today is Sunday.

2582
04:23:26,749 --> 04:23:32,462
Do you know that the doctor says
you must very soon be in heaven?

2583
04:23:35,424 --> 04:23:41,846
Do you not feel willing to acquiesce in
God's allotment if he wills you to go today?

2584
04:23:47,686 --> 04:23:54,734
l prefer it.

2585
04:23:57,780 --> 04:23:59,072
Well. . .

2586
04:24:01,033 --> 04:24:04,035
. ..by the time this day closes. . .

2587
04:24:05,287 --> 04:24:08,456
. ..you will be with the blessed
Savior in his glory.

2588
04:24:08,624 --> 04:24:09,833
[SOBBlNG]

2589
04:24:12,586 --> 04:24:13,837
l ....

2590
04:24:15,798 --> 04:24:22,095
l will be an infinite gainer
to be translated.

2591
04:24:53,127 --> 04:24:54,752
General Lee.

2592
04:25:00,759 --> 04:25:02,802
What is the news, Reverend?

2593
04:25:02,970 --> 04:25:07,473
General Lee, l must report
that his case appears hopeless.

2594
04:25:09,935 --> 04:25:14,355
His wounds are healing,
but he's dying of pneumonia.

2595
04:25:17,401 --> 04:25:21,362
Surely General Jackson must recover.

2596
04:25:22,031 --> 04:25:26,826
God will not take him from us, not now
that we need him so very much.

2597
04:25:31,248 --> 04:25:33,499
Will you see him, sir?

2598
04:25:35,377 --> 04:25:38,004
No, sir, l won't. No, sir.

2599
04:25:47,222 --> 04:25:50,433
When you return,
l trust you'll find him better.

2600
04:25:53,020 --> 04:25:59,150
And when the occasion offers, tell him
that l prayed for him last night.. .

2601
04:26:01,904 --> 04:26:07,158
. ..as l never prayed,
l believe, for myself.

2602
04:26:08,202 --> 04:26:14,874
Please tell him.

2603
